CollisionPolygon2D.name: CollisionPolygon2D
CollisionPolygon2D.description: Provides a 2D collision polygon to a [CollisionObject2D] parent. Polygon can be drawn in the editor or specified by a list of vertices.

methods.name: get_build_mode
methods.description: Return whether the polygon is a [ConvexPolygonShape2D] ([code]build_mode==0[/code]), or a [ConcavePolygonShape2D] ([code]build_mode==1[/code]).

methods.name: get_polygon
methods.description: Return the list of points that define the polygon.

methods.name: set_build_mode
methods.description: Set whether the polygon is to be a [ConvexPolygonShape2D] ([code]build_mode==0[/code]), or a [ConcavePolygonShape2D] ([code]build_mode==1[/code]).

methods.name: set_polygon
methods.description:
Set the array of points forming the polygon.
				When editing the point list via the editor, depending on [method get_build_mode], it has to be a list of points (for [code]build_mode==0[/code]), or a list of lines (for [code]build_mode==1[/code]). In the second case, the even elements of the array define the start point of the line, and the odd elements the end point.

constants.name: BUILD_SOLIDS
constants.description: Collisions will include the polygon and its contained area.

constants.name: BUILD_SEGMENTS
constants.description: Collisions will only include the polygon edges.

properties.name: build_mode
properties.description: Collision build mode. Use one of the [code]BUILD_*[/code] constants. Default value: [code]BUILD_SOLIDS[/code].

properties.name: disabled
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] no collisions will be detected.

properties.name: one_way_collision
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] only edges that face up, relative to CollisionPolygon2D's rotation, will collide with other objects.

properties.name: polygon
properties.description: The polygon's list of vertices. The final point will be connected to the first.

StyleBoxFlat.name: StyleBoxFlat
StyleBoxFlat.brief_description: Customizable Stylebox with a given set of parameters. (no texture required)
StyleBoxFlat.description:
This stylebox can be used to achieve all kinds of looks without the need of a texture. Those properties are customizable:
		 - Color
		 - Border width (individual width for each border)
		 - Rounded corners (individual radius for each corner)
		 - Shadow
		 About corner radius:
		 	Setting corner radius to high values is allowed. As soon as corners would overlap the stylebox will switch to a relative system. Example:
			[codeblock]
			height = 30
			corner_radius_top_left = 50
			corner_radius_bottom_left = 100
			[/codeblock]
			The relative system now would take the 1:2 ratio of the two left corners to calculate the actual corner width. Both corners added will [b]never[/b] be more than the height. Result:
			[codeblock]
			corner_radius_top_left: 10
			corner_radius_bottom_left: 20
			[/codeblock]

properties.name: anti_aliasing
properties.description: Anti Aliasing draws a small ring around edges. This ring fades to transparent. As a result edges look much smoother. This is only noticeable when using rounded corners.

properties.name: anti_aliasing_size
properties.description: This changes the size of the faded ring. Higher values can be used to achieve a "blurry" effect.

properties.name: bg_color
properties.description: The background color of the stylebox.

properties.name: border_blend
properties.description: When set to true, the border will fade into the background color.

properties.name: border_color
properties.description: Sets the color of the border.

properties.name: border_width_bottom
properties.description: Border width for the bottom border.

properties.name: border_width_left
properties.description: Border width for the left border.

properties.name: border_width_right
properties.description: Border width for the right border.

properties.name: border_width_top
properties.description: Border width for the top border.

properties.name: corner_detail
properties.description:
This sets the amount of vertices used for each corner. Higher values result in rounder corners but take more processing power to compute. When choosing a value you should take the corner radius ([method set_corner_radius]) into account.
			For corner radius smaller than 10: 4-5 should be enough
			For corner radius smaller than 30: 8-12 should be enough ...

properties.name: corner_radius_bottom_left
properties.description: The corner radius of the bottom left corner. When set to 0 the corner is not rounded.

properties.name: corner_radius_bottom_right
properties.description: The corner radius of the bottom right corner. When set to 0 the corner is not rounded.

properties.name: corner_radius_top_left
properties.description: The corner radius of the top left corner. When set to 0 the corner is not rounded.

properties.name: corner_radius_top_right
properties.description: The corner radius of the top right corner. When set to 0 the corner is not rounded.

properties.name: draw_center
properties.description: Toggels drawing of the inner part of the stylebox.

properties.name: expand_margin_bottom
properties.description: Expands the stylebox outside of the control rect on the bottom edge. Useful in combination with border_width_bottom. To draw a border outside the control rect.

properties.name: expand_margin_left
properties.description: Expands the stylebox outside of the control rect on the left edge. Useful in combination with border_width_left. To draw a border outside the control rect.

properties.name: expand_margin_right
properties.description: Expands the stylebox outside of the control rect on the right edge. Useful in combination with border_width_right. To draw a border outside the control rect.

properties.name: expand_margin_top
properties.description: Expands the stylebox outside of the control rect on the top edge. Useful in combination with border_width_top. To draw a border outside the control rect.

properties.name: shadow_color
properties.description: The color of the shadow. (This has no effect when shadow_size < 1)

properties.name: shadow_size
properties.description: The shadow size in pixels.

constants.name: AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_DISABLED
constants.description: This area does not affect gravity/damp. These are generally areas that exist only to detect collisions, and objects entering or exiting them.

constants.name: AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_COMBINE
constants.description: This area adds its gravity/damp values to whatever has been calculated so far. This way, many overlapping areas can combine their physics to make interesting effects.

constants.name: AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_COMBINE_REPLACE
constants.description: This area adds its gravity/damp values to whatever has been calculated so far. Then stops taking into account the rest of the areas, even the default one.

constants.name: AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_REPLACE
constants.description: This area replaces any gravity/damp, even the default one, and stops taking into account the rest of the areas.

constants.name: AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_REPLACE_COMBINE
constants.description: This area replaces any gravity/damp calculated so far, but keeps calculating the rest of the areas, down to the default one.

Physics2DDirectSpaceState.name: Physics2DDirectSpaceState
Physics2DDirectSpaceState.brief_description: Direct access object to a space in the [Physics2DServer].
Physics2DDirectSpaceState.description: Direct access object to a space in the [Physics2DServer]. It's used mainly to do queries against objects and areas residing in a given space.

methods.name: cast_motion
methods.description:
Check whether the shape can travel to a point. If it can, the method will return an array with two floats: The first is the distance the shape can move in that direction without colliding, and the second is the distance at which it will collide.
	If the shape can not move, the array will be empty.

methods.name: collide_shape
methods.description: Check the intersections of a shape, given through a [Physics2DShapeQueryParameters] object, against the space. The resulting array contains a list of points where the shape intersects another. Like with [method intersect_shape], the number of returned results can be limited to save processing time.

methods.name: get_rest_info
methods.description:
Check the intersections of a shape, given through a [Physics2DShapeQueryParameters] object, against the space. If it collides with more than a shape, the nearest one is selected. The returned object is a dictionary containing the following fields:
				pointo: Place where the shapes intersect.
				normal: Normal of the object at the point where the shapes intersect.
				shape: Shape index within the object against which the shape intersected.
				metadata: Metadata of the shape against which the shape intersected. This metadata is different from [method Object.get_meta], and is set with [method Physics2DServer.shape_set_data].
				collider_id: Id of the object against which the shape intersected.
				collider: Object against which the shape intersected.
				rid: [RID] of the object against which the shape intersected.
				linear_velocity: The movement vector of the object the shape intersected, if it was a body. If it was an area, it is (0,0).
				If the shape did not intersect anything, then an empty dictionary (dir.empty()==true) is returned instead.

methods.name: intersect_point
methods.description:
Check whether a point is inside any shape. The shapes the point is inside of are returned in an array containing dictionaries with the following fields:
				shape: Shape index within the object the point is in.
				metadata: Metadata of the shape the point is in. This metadata is different from [method Object.get_meta], and is set with [method Physics2DServer.shape_set_data].
				collider_id: Id of the object the point is in.
				collider: Object the point is inside of.
				rid: [RID] of the object the point is in.
				Additionally, the method can take an array of objects or [RID]\ s that are to be excluded from collisions, a bitmask representing the physics layers to check in, and another bitmask for the types of objects to check (see TYPE_MASK_* constants).

methods.name: intersect_ray
methods.description:
Intersect a ray in a given space. The returned object is a dictionary with the following fields:
				position: Place where ray is stopped.
				normal: Normal of the object at the point where the ray was stopped.
				shape: Shape index within the object against which the ray was stopped.
				metadata: Metadata of the shape against which the ray was stopped. This metadata is different from [method Object.get_meta], and is set with [method Physics2DServer.shape_set_data].
				collider_id: Id of the object against which the ray was stopped.
				collider: Object against which the ray was stopped.
				rid: [RID] of the object against which the ray was stopped.
				If the ray did not intersect anything, then an empty dictionary (dir.empty()==true) is returned instead.
				Additionally, the method can take an array of objects or [RID]\ s that are to be excluded from collisions, a bitmask representing the physics layers to check in, and another bitmask for the types of objects to check (see TYPE_MASK_* constants).

methods.name: intersect_shape
methods.description:
Check the intersections of a shape, given through a [Physics2DShapeQueryParameters] object, against the space. The intersected shapes are returned in an array containing dictionaries with the following fields:
				shape: Shape index within the object the shape intersected.
				metadata: Metadata of the shape intersected by the shape given through the [Physics2DShapeQueryParameters]. This metadata is different from [method Object.get_meta], and is set with [method Physics2DServer.shape_set_data].
				collider_id: Id of the object the shape intersected.
				collider: Object the shape intersected.
				rid: [RID] of the object the shape intersected.
				The number of intersections can be limited with the second parameter, to reduce the processing time.

constants.name: TYPE_MASK_STATIC_BODY
constants.description: Check for collisions with static bodies.

constants.name: TYPE_MASK_KINEMATIC_BODY
constants.description: Check for collisions with kinematic bodies.

constants.name: TYPE_MASK_RIGID_BODY
constants.description: Check for collisions with rigid bodies.

constants.name: TYPE_MASK_CHARACTER_BODY
constants.description: Check for collisions with rigid bodies in character mode.

constants.name: TYPE_MASK_AREA

constants.name: TYPE_MASK_COLLISION

StaticBody.name: StaticBody
StaticBody.description:
Static body for 3D Physics. A static body is a simple body that is not intended to move. They don't consume any CPU resources in contrast to a [RigidBody3D] so they are great for scenario collision.
		A static body can also be animated by using simulated motion mode. This is useful for implementing functionalities such as moving platforms. When this mode is active the body can be animated and automatically computes linear and angular velocity to apply in that frame and to influence other bodies.
		Alternatively, a constant linear or angular velocity can be set for the static body, so even if it doesn't move, it affects other bodies as if it was moving (this is useful for simulating conveyor belts or conveyor wheels).

methods.name: get_bounce
methods.description: Return the body bounciness.

methods.name: get_constant_angular_velocity
methods.description: Return the constant angular velocity for the body.

methods.name: get_constant_linear_velocity
methods.description: Return the constant linear velocity for the body.

methods.name: get_friction
methods.description: Return the body friction.

methods.name: set_bounce
methods.description: Set the body bounciness, from 0 (not bouncy) to 1 (bouncy).

methods.name: set_constant_angular_velocity
methods.description: Set a constant angular velocity for the body. This does not rotate the body, but affects other bodies touching it, as if it was rotating.

methods.name: set_constant_linear_velocity
methods.description: Set a constant linear velocity for the body. This does not move the body, but affects other bodies touching it, as if it was moving.

methods.name: set_friction
methods.description: Set the body friction, from 0 (frictionless) to 1 (full friction).

properties.name: bounce
properties.description: The body bounciness.

properties.name: constant_angular_velocity
properties.description: The constant angular velocity for the body. This does not rotate the body, but affects other bodies that touch it, as if it was in a state of rotation.

properties.name: constant_linear_velocity
properties.description: The constant linear velocity for the body. This does not move the body, but affects other bodies that touch it, as if it was in a state of movement.

properties.name: friction
properties.description: The body friction, from 0 (frictionless) to 1 (full friction).

methods.name: blend_rect_mask
methods.description: Alpha-blends a "src_rect" [Rect2] from "src" [Image] to this [Image] using a "mask" [Image] on coordinates "dest". Alpha channels are required for both "src" and "mask", dest pixels and src pixels will blend if the corresponding mask pixel's alpha value is not 0. "src" [Image] and "mask" [Image] *must* have the same size (width and height) but they can have different formats

Alpha channel is required for "mask", will copy src pixel onto dest if the corresponding mask pixel's alpha value is not 0. "src" [Image] and "mask" [Image] *must* have the same size (width and height) but they can have different formats

Curve3D.name: Curve3D
Curve3D.brief_description: Describes a Bezier curve in 3D space.
Curve3D.description:
This class describes a Bezier curve in 3D space. It is mainly used to give a shape to a [Path], but can be manually sampled for other purposes.
		It keeps a cache of precalculated points along the curve, to speed further calculations up.

methods.name: add_point
methods.description:
Adds a point to a curve, at "position", with control points "in" and "out".
				If "at_position" is given, the point is inserted before the point number "at_position", moving that point (and every point after) after the inserted point. If "at_position" is not given, or is an illegal value (at_position <0 or at_position >= [method get_point_count]), the point will be appended at the end of the point list.

methods.name: get_bake_interval
methods.description: Returns the distance between two adjacent cached points.

methods.name: get_baked_length
methods.description: Returns the total length of the curve, based on the cached points. Given enough density (see [method set_bake_interval]), it should be approximate enough.

methods.name: get_baked_points
methods.description: Returns the cache of points as a [PoolVector3Array].

methods.name: get_baked_tilts
methods.description: Returns the cache of tilts as a [RealArray].

methods.name: get_point_count
methods.description: Returns the number of points describing the curve.

methods.name: get_point_in
methods.description: Returns the position of the control point leading to the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0, 0).

methods.name: get_point_out
methods.description: Returns the position of the control point leading out of the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0, 0).

methods.name: get_point_position
methods.description: Returns the position of the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0, 0).

methods.name: get_point_tilt
methods.description: Returns the tilt angle in radians for the point "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns 0.

methods.name: interpolate
methods.description:
Returns the position between the vertex "idx" and the vertex "idx"+1, where "t" controls if the point is the first vertex (t = 0.0), the last vertex (t = 1.0), or in between. Values of "t" outside the range (0.0 >= t  <=1) give strange, but predictable results.
				If "idx" is out of bounds it is truncated to the first or last vertex, and "t" is ignored. If the curve has no points, the function sends an error to the console, and returns (0, 0, 0).

methods.name: interpolate_baked
methods.description:
Returns a point within the curve at position "offset", where "offset" is measured as a distance in 3D units along the curve.
				To do that, it finds the two cached points where the "offset" lies between, then interpolates the values. This interpolation is cubic if "cubic" is set to true, or linear if set to false.
				Cubic interpolation tends to follow the curves better, but linear is faster (and often, precise enough).

methods.name: interpolatef
methods.description: Returns the position at the vertex "fofs". It calls [method interpolate] using the integer part of fofs as "idx", and its fractional part as "t".

methods.name: remove_point
methods.description: Deletes the point "idx" from the curve. Sends an error to the console if "idx" is out of bounds.

methods.name: set_bake_interval
methods.description: Sets the distance in 3D units between two adjacent cached points. Changing it forces the cache to be recomputed the next time a xxx_baked_xxx function is called. The less distance, the more points the cache will have, and the more memory it will consume, so use with care.

methods.name: set_point_in
methods.description: Sets the position of the control point leading to the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: set_point_out
methods.description: Sets the position of the control point leading out of the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: set_point_position
methods.description: Sets the position for the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: set_point_tilt
methods.description:
Sets the tilt angle in radians for the point "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.
				The tilt controls the rotation along the look-at axis an object traveling the path would have. In the case of a curve controlling a [PathFollow], this tilt is an offset over the natural tilt the PathFollow calculates.

methods.name: tessellate
methods.description:
Returns a list of points along the curve, with a curvature controlled point density. That is, the curvier parts will have more points than the straighter parts.
				This approximation makes straight segments between each point, then subdivides those segments until the resulting shape is similar enough.
				"max_stages" controls how many subdivisions a curve segment may face before it is considered approximate enough. Each subdivision splits the segment in half, so the default 5 stages may mean up to 32 subdivisions per curve segment. Increase with care!
				"tolerance_degrees" controls how many degrees the midpoint of a segment may deviate from the real curve, before the segment has to be subdivided.

PathFollow.name: PathFollow
PathFollow.description:
This node takes its parent [Path], and returns the coordinates of a point within it, given a distance from the first vertex.
		It is useful for making other nodes follow a path, without coding the movement pattern. For that, the nodes must be descendants of this node. Then, when setting an offset in this node, the descendant nodes will move accordingly.

methods.name: get_cubic_interpolation
methods.description: This method returns whether the position between two cached points (see [method set_cubic_interpolation]) is interpolated linearly, or cubicly.

methods.name: get_h_offset
methods.description: Returns the X displacement this node has from its parent [Path].

methods.name: get_offset
methods.description: Returns the distance along the path in 3D units.

methods.name: get_rotation_mode
methods.description: Returns the rotation mode. The constants below list which axes are allowed to rotate for each mode.

methods.name: get_unit_offset
methods.description: Returns the distance along the path as a number in the range 0.0 (for the first vertex) to 1.0 (for the last).

methods.name: get_v_offset
methods.description: Returns the Y displacement this node has from its parent [Path].

methods.name: has_loop
methods.description: Returns whether this node wraps its offsets around, or truncates them to the path ends.

methods.name: set_cubic_interpolation
methods.description:
The points along the [Curve3D] of the [Path] are precomputed before use, for faster calculations. The point at the requested offset is then calculated interpolating between two adjacent cached points. This may present a problem if the curve makes sharp turns, as the cached points may not follow the curve closely enough.
				There are two answers to this problem: Either increase the number of cached points and increase memory consumption, or make a cubic interpolation between two points at the cost of (slightly) slower calculations.
				This method controls whether the position between two cached points is interpolated linearly, or cubicly.

methods.name: set_h_offset
methods.description:
Moves this node in the X axis. As this node's position will be set every time its offset is set, this allows many PathFollow to share the same curve (and thus the same movement pattern), yet not return the same position for a given path offset.
				A similar effect may be achieved moving the this node's descendants.

methods.name: set_loop
methods.description: If set, any offset outside the path's length (whether set by [method set_offset] or [method set_unit_offset] will wrap around, instead of stopping at the ends. Set it for cyclic paths.

methods.name: set_offset
methods.description: Sets the distance from the first vertex, measured in 3D units along the path. This sets this node's position to a point within the path.

methods.name: set_rotation_mode
methods.description: Allows or forbids rotation on one or more axes, per the constants below.

methods.name: set_unit_offset
methods.description: Sets the distance from the first vertex, considering 0.0 as the first vertex and 1.0 as the last. This is just another way of expressing the offset within the path, as the offset supplied is multiplied internally by the path's length.

methods.name: set_v_offset
methods.description: Moves this node in the Y axis, for the same reasons of [method set_h_offset].

constants.name: ROTATION_NONE
constants.description: Forbids the PathFollow to rotate.

constants.name: ROTATION_Y
constants.description: Allows the PathFollow to rotate in the Y axis only.

constants.name: ROTATION_XY
constants.description: Allows the PathFollow to rotate in both the X, and Y axes.

constants.name: ROTATION_XYZ
constants.description: Allows the PathFollow to rotate in any axis.

SurfaceTool.name: SurfaceTool
SurfaceTool.description:
The [SurfaceTool] is used to construct a [Mesh] by specifying vertex attributes individually. It can be used to construct a [Mesh] from script. All properties except index need to be added before a call to [method add_vertex]. For example adding vertex colors and UVs looks like
		[codeblock]
		var st = SurfaceTool.new()
		st.begin(Mesh.PRIMITIVE_TRIANGLES)
		st.add_color(Color(1, 0, 0))
		st.add_uv(Vector2(0, 0))
		st.add_vertex(Vector3(0, 0, 0))
		[/codeblock]
		The [SurfaceTool] now contains one vertex of a triangle which has a UV coordinate and a specified [Color]. If another vertex were added without calls to [method add_uv] or [method add_color] then the last values would be used.
		It is very important that vertex attributes are passed [b]before[/b] the call to [method add_vertex], failure to do this will result in an error when committing the vertex information to a mesh.

methods.name: add_bones
methods.description: Add an array of bones for the next Vertex to use.

methods.name: add_color
methods.description: Specify a [Color] for the next Vertex to use.

methods.name: add_index
methods.description: Adds an index to index array if you are using indexed Vertices. Does not need to be called before adding Vertex.

methods.name: add_normal
methods.description: Specify a normal for the next Vertex to use.

methods.name: add_smooth_group
methods.description: Specify whether current Vertex (if using only Vertex arrays) or current index (if also using index arrays) should utilize smooth normals for normal calculation.

methods.name: add_tangent
methods.description: Specify a Tangent for the next Vertex to use.

methods.name: add_triangle_fan
methods.description: Insert a triangle fan made of array data into [Mesh] being constructed.

methods.name: add_uv
methods.description: Specify UV Coordinate for next Vertex to use.

methods.name: add_uv2
methods.description: Specify an optional second set of UV coordinates for next Vertex to use.

methods.name: add_vertex
methods.description: Specify position of current Vertex. Should be called after specifying other vertex properties (e.g. Color, UV).

methods.name: add_weights
methods.description: Specify weight value for next Vertex to use.

methods.name: begin
methods.description: Called before adding any Vertices. Takes the primitive type as an argument (e.g. Mesh.PRIMITIVE_TRIANGLES).

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear all information passed into the surface tool so far.

methods.name: commit
methods.description: Returns a constructed [ArrayMesh] from current information passed in. If an existing [ArrayMesh] is passed in as an argument, will add an extra surface to the existing [ArrayMesh].

methods.name: deindex
methods.description: Removes index array by expanding Vertex array.

methods.name: generate_normals
methods.description: Generates normals from Vertices so you do not have to do it manually.

methods.name: index
methods.description: Shrinks Vertex array by creating an index array. Avoids reusing Vertices.

methods.name: set_material
methods.description: Sets [Material] to be used by the [Mesh] you are constructing.

Performance.name: Performance
Performance.description:
This class provides access to a number of different monitors related to performance, such as memory usage, draw calls, and FPS. These are the same as the values displayed in the [i]Monitor[/i] tab in the editor's [i]Debugger[/i] panel. By using the [method get_monitor] method of this class, you can access this data from your code. Note that a few of these monitors are only available in debug mode and will always return 0 when used in a release build.
		Many of these monitors are not updated in real-time, so there may be a short delay between changes.

methods.name: get_monitor
methods.description:
Returns the value of one of the available monitors. You should provide one of this class's constants as the argument, like this:
				[codeblock]
				print(Performance.get_monitor(Performance.TIME_FPS)) # Prints the FPS to the console
				[/codeblock]

constants.name: TIME_PHYSICS_PROCESS

constants.name: RENDER_VIDEO_MEM_USED

constants.name: RENDER_TEXTURE_MEM_USED

constants.name: RENDER_VERTEX_MEM_USED

constants.name: PHYSICS_2D_ACTIVE_OBJECTS

constants.name: PHYSICS_3D_COLLISION_PAIRS
constants.description: Number of collision pairs in the 3D physics engine.

constants.name: PHYSICS_3D_ISLAND_COUNT
constants.description: Number of islands in the 3D physics engine.

ConcavePolygonShape.description: Concave polygon shape resource, which can be set into a [PhysicsBody] or area. This shape is created by feeding a list of triangles.

methods.name: set_faces
methods.description: Set the faces (an array of triangles).

Line2D.name: Line2D
Line2D.description: A line through several points in 2D space.

methods.name: add_point
methods.description: Add a point at the [code]position[/code]. Appends the point at the end of the line.

methods.name: get_point_count
methods.description: Returns the Line2D's amount of points.

methods.name: get_point_position
methods.description: Returns point [code]i[code]'s position.

methods.name: remove_point
methods.description: Remove the point at index [code]i[/code] from the line.

methods.name: set_point_position
methods.description: Overwites the position in point [code]i[/code] with the supplied [code]position[/code].

constants.name: LINE_JOINT_SHARP
constants.description: The line's joints will be pointy. If [code]sharp_limit[/code] is greater than the rotation of a joint, it becomes a bevel joint instead.

constants.name: LINE_JOINT_BEVEL
constants.description: The line's joints will be bevelled/chamfered.

constants.name: LINE_JOINT_ROUND
constants.description: The line's joints will be rounded.

constants.name: LINE_CAP_NONE
constants.description: Don't have a line cap.

constants.name: LINE_CAP_BOX
constants.description: Draws the line cap as a box.

constants.name: LINE_CAP_ROUND
constants.description: Draws the line cap as a circle.

constants.name: LINE_TEXTURE_NONE
constants.description: Takes the left pixels of the texture and renders it over the whole line.

constants.name: LINE_TEXTURE_TILE
constants.description: Tiles the texture over the line. The texture need to be imported with Repeat Enabled for it to work properly.

properties.name: begin_cap_mode
properties.description: Controls the style of the line's first point. Use [code]LINE_CAP_*[/code] constants. Default value: [code]LINE_CAP_NONE[/code].

properties.name: default_color
properties.description: The line's color. Will not be used if a gradient is set.

properties.name: end_cap_mode
properties.description: Controls the style of the line's last point. Use [code]LINE_CAP_*[/code] constants. Default value: [code]LINE_CAP_NONE[/code].

properties.name: gradient
properties.description: The gradient is drawn through the whole line from start to finish. The default color will not be used if a gradient is set.

properties.name: joint_mode
properties.description: The style for the points inbetween the start and the end.

properties.name: points
properties.description: The points that form the lines. The line is drawn between every point set in this array.

properties.name: round_precision
properties.description: The smoothness of the rounded joints and caps. This is only used if a cap or joint is set as round.

properties.name: sharp_limit
properties.description: The direction difference in radians between vector points. This value is only used if [code]joint mode[/code] is set to [code]LINE_JOINT_SHARP[/code].

properties.name: texture
properties.description: The texture used for the line's texture. Uses [code]texture_mode[/code] for drawing style.

properties.name: texture_mode
properties.description: The style to render the [code]texture[/code] on the line. Use [code]LINE_TEXTURE_*[/code] constants. Default value: [code]LINE_TEXTURE_NONE[/code].

properties.name: width
properties.description: The line's width.

AudioEffectEQ10.name: AudioEffectEQ10
AudioEffectEQ10.brief_description:
Adds a 10-band equalizer audio effect to an Audio bus. Gives you control over frequencies from 31 Hz to 16000 Hz.
		Each frequency can be modulated between -60/+24 dB.
AudioEffectEQ10.description:
Frequency bands :
		Band 1 : 31 Hz
		Band 2 : 62 Hz
		Band 3 : 125 Hz
		Band 4 : 250 Hz
		Band 5 : 500 Hz
		Band 6 : 1000 Hz
		Band 7 : 2000 Hz
		Band 8 : 4000 Hz
		Band 9 : 8000 Hz
		Band 10 : 16000 Hz

		See also [AudioEffectEQ], [AudioEffectEQ6], [AudioEffectEQ21].

WorldEnvironment.name: WorldEnvironment
WorldEnvironment.brief_description: Sets environment properties for the entire scene
WorldEnvironment.description: The [WorldEnvironment] node can be added to a scene in order to set default [Environment] variables for the scene. The [WorldEnvironment] can be overridden by an [Environment] node set on the current [Camera]. Additionally, only one [WorldEnvironment] may be instanced in a given scene at a time. The [WorldEnvironment] allows the user to specify default lighting parameters (e.g. ambient lighting), various post-processing effects (e.g. SSAO, DOF, Tonemapping), and how to draw the background (e.g. solid color, skybox).

methods.name: set_environment

methods.description:
Returns a point within the curve at position "offset", where "offset" is measured as a pixel distance along the curve.
				To do that, it finds the two cached points where the "offset" lies between, then interpolates the values. This interpolation is cubic if "cubic" is set to true, or linear if set to false.
				Cubic interpolation tends to follow the curves better, but linear is faster (and often, precise enough).

methods.name: interpolatef
methods.description: Returns the position at the vertex "fofs". It calls [method interpolate] using the integer part of fofs as "idx", and its fractional part as "t".

methods.name: remove_point
methods.description: Deletes the point "idx" from the curve. Sends an error to the console if "idx" is out of bounds.

methods.name: set_bake_interval
methods.description: Sets the distance in pixels between two adjacent cached points. Changing it forces the cache to be recomputed the next time a xxx_baked_xxx function is called. The less distance, the more points the cache will have, and the more memory it will consume, so use with care.

methods.name: set_point_in
methods.description: Sets the position of the control point leading to the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: set_point_out
methods.description: Sets the position of the control point leading out of the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: set_point_position
methods.description: Sets the position for the vertex "idx". If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console.

methods.name: tessellate
methods.description:
Returns a list of points along the curve, with a curvature controlled point density. That is, the curvier parts will have more points than the straighter parts.
				This approximation makes straight segments between each point, then subdivides those segments until the resulting shape is similar enough.
				"max_stages" controls how many subdivisions a curve segment may face before it is considered approximate enough. Each subdivision splits the segment in half, so the default 5 stages may mean up to 32 subdivisions per curve segment. Increase with care!
				"tolerance_degrees" controls how many degrees the midpoint of a segment may deviate from the real curve, before the segment has to be subdivided.

FileDialog.name: FileDialog
FileDialog.brief_description: Dialog for selecting files or directories in the filesystem.
FileDialog.description: FileDialog is a preset dialog used to choose files and directories in the filesystem. It supports filter masks.

methods.name: add_filter
methods.description: Add a custom filter. Filter format is: "mask ; description", example (C++): dialog->add_filter("*.png ; PNG Images");

methods.name: clear_filters
methods.description: Clear all the added filters in the dialog.

methods.name: get_access
methods.description: Return the file access permission of the dialog.

methods.name: get_current_dir
methods.description: Get the current working directory of the file dialog.

methods.name: get_current_file
methods.description: Get the current selected file of the file dialog (empty if none).

methods.name: get_current_path
methods.description: Get the current selected path (directory and file) of the file dialog (empty if none).

methods.name: get_mode
methods.description: Get the file dialog mode from the MODE_* enum.

methods.name: get_vbox
methods.description: Return the vertical box container of the dialog, custom controls can be added to it.

methods.name: invalidate
methods.description: Invalidate and update the current dialog content list.

methods.name: is_showing_hidden_files
methods.description: Return true if the dialog allows show hidden files.

methods.name: set_access
methods.description: Set the file access permission of the dialog(Must be one of [ACCESS_RESOURCES], [ACCESS_USERDATA] or [ACCESS_FILESYSTEM]).

methods.name: set_current_dir
methods.description: Set the current working directory of the file dialog.

methods.name: set_current_file
methods.description: Set the current selected file name of the file dialog.

methods.name: set_current_path
methods.description: Set the current selected file path of the file dialog.

methods.name: set_mode
methods.description: Set the file dialog mode from the MODE_* enum.

methods.name: set_show_hidden_files
methods.description: Set the dialog should show hidden files.

signals.name: dir_selected
signals.description: Event emitted when the user selects a directory.

signals.name: file_selected
signals.description: Event emitted when the user selects a file (double clicks it or presses the OK button).

signals.name: files_selected
signals.description: Event emitted when the user selects multiple files.

constants.name: MODE_OPEN_FILE
constants.description: The dialog allows the selection of one, and only one file.

constants.name: MODE_OPEN_FILES
constants.description: The dialog allows the selection of multiple files.

constants.name: MODE_OPEN_DIR
constants.description: The dialog functions as a folder selector, disallowing the selection of any file.

constants.name: MODE_OPEN_ANY
constants.description: The dialog allows the selection of a file or a directory.

constants.name: MODE_SAVE_FILE
constants.description: The dialog will warn when a file exists.

constants.name: ACCESS_RESOURCES
constants.description: The dialog allows the selection of file and directory.

constants.name: ACCESS_USERDATA
constants.description: The dialog allows access files under [Resource] path(res://) .

constants.name: ACCESS_FILESYSTEM
constants.description: The dialog allows access files in whole file system.

Joint2D.name: Joint2D
Joint2D.brief_description: Base node for all joint constraints in 2D physics.
Joint2D.description: Base node for all joint constraints in 2D physics. Joints take 2 bodies and apply a custom constraint.

methods.name: get_node_a
methods.description: Return the path to the A node for the joint.

methods.name: get_node_b
methods.description: Return the path to the B node for the joint.

methods.name: set_node_a
methods.description: Set the path to the A node for the joint. Must be of type [PhysicsBody2D].

methods.name: set_node_b
methods.description: Set the path to the B node for the joint. Must be of type [PhysicsBody2D].

Tween.name: Tween
Tween.brief_description: Node useful for animations with unknown start and end points.
Tween.description:
Node useful for animations with unknown start and end points, procedural animations, making one node follow another, and other simple behavior.
		Because it is easy to get it wrong, here is a quick usage example:
		[codeblock]
		var tween = get_node("Tween")
		tween.interpolate_property(get_node("Node2D_to_move"), "transform/origin", Vector2(0,0), Vector2(100,100), 1, Tween.TRANS_LINEAR, Tween.EASE_IN_OUT)
		tween.start()
		[/codeblock]
		Some of the methods of this class require a property name. You can get the property name by hovering over the property in the inspector of the editor.
		Many of the methods accept [code]trans_type[/code] and [code]ease_type[/code]. The first accepts an TRANS_* constant, and refers to the way the timing of the animation is handled (you might want to see [code]http://easings.net/[/code] for some examples). The second accepts an EASE_* constant, and controls the where [code]trans_type[/code] is applied to the interpolation (in the beginning, the end, or both). If you don't know which transition and easing to pick, you can try different TRANS_* constants with EASE_IN_OUT, and use the one that looks best.

methods.name: follow_method
methods.description:
Follow [code]method[/code] of [code]object[/code] and apply the returned value on [code]target_method[/code] of [code]target[/code], beginning from [code]initial_val[/code] for [code]duration[/code] seconds, [code]delay[/code] later. Methods are animated by calling them with consequitive values.
				[code]trans_type[/code] accepts TRANS_* constants, and is the way the animation is interpolated, while [code]ease_type[/code] accepts EASE_* constants, and controls the place of the interpolation (the beginning, the end, or both). You can read more about them in the class description.

methods.name: follow_property
methods.description:
Follow [code]property[/code] of [code]object[/code] and apply it on [code]target_property[/code] of [code]target[/code], beginning from [code]initial_val[/code] for [code]duration[/code] seconds, [code]delay[/code] seconds later. Note that [code]target:target_property[/code] would equal [code]object:property[/code] at the end of the tween.
				[code]trans_type[/code] accepts TRANS_* constants, and is the way the animation is interpolated, while [code]ease_type[/code] accepts EASE_* constants, and controls the place of the interpolation (the beginning, the end, or both). You can read more about them in the class description.

methods.name: get_runtime
methods.description: Returns the time needed for all tweens to end in seconds, measured from the start. Thus, if you have two tweens, one ending 10 seconds after the start and the other - 20 seconds, it would return 20 seconds, as by that time all tweens would have finished.

methods.name: get_speed_scale
methods.description: Returns the speed that has been set from editor GUI or [method set_repeat].

methods.name: get_tween_process_mode
methods.description: Returns the process mode that has been set from editor GUI or [method set_tween_process_mode]

methods.name: interpolate_callback
methods.description: Call [code]callback[/code] of [code]object[/code] after [code]duration[/code]. [code]arg1[/code]-[code]arg5[/code] are arguments to be passed to the callback.

methods.name: interpolate_deferred_callback
methods.description: Call [code]callback[/code] of [code]object[/code] after [code]duration[/code] on the main thread (similar to [method Object.call_deferred]). [code]arg1[/code]-[code]arg5[/code] are arguments to be passed to the callback.

methods.name: interpolate_method
methods.description:
Animate [code]method[/code] of [code]object[/code] from [code]initial_val[/code] to [code]final_val[/code] for [code]duration[/code] seconds, [code]delay[/code] seconds later. Methods are animated by calling them with consecutive values.
				[code]trans_type[/code] accepts TRANS_* constants, and is the way the animation is interpolated, while [code]ease_type[/code] accepts EASE_* constants, and controls the place of the interpolation (the beginning, the end, or both). You can read more about them in the class description.

methods.name: interpolate_property
methods.description:
Animate [code]property[/code] of [code]object[/code] from [code]initial_val[/code] to [code]final_val[/code] for [code]duration[/code] seconds, [code]delay[/code] seconds later.
				[code]trans_type[/code] accepts TRANS_* constants, and is the way the animation is interpolated, while [code]ease_type[/code] accepts EASE_* constants, and controls the place of the interpolation (the beginning, the end, or both). You can read more about them in the class description.

methods.name: is_active
methods.description: Returns true if any tweens are currently running, and false otherwise. Note that this method doesn't consider tweens that have ended.

methods.name: is_repeat
methods.description: Returns true if repeat has been set from editor GUI or [method set_repeat].

methods.name: remove
methods.description: Stop animating and completely remove a tween, given its object and property/method pair. Passing empty String as key will remove all tweens for given object.

methods.name: remove_all
methods.description: Stop animating and completely remove all tweens.

methods.name: reset
methods.description: Resets a tween to the initial value (the one given, not the one before the tween), given its object and property/method pair. Passing empty String as key will reset all tweens for given object.

methods.name: reset_all
methods.description: Resets all tweens to their initial values (the ones given, not those before the tween).

methods.name: resume
methods.description: Continue animating a stopped tween, given its object and property/method pair. Passing empty String as key will resume all tweens for given object.

methods.name: resume_all
methods.description: Continue animating all stopped tweens.

methods.name: seek
methods.description: Seek the animation to the given [code]time[/code] in seconds.

methods.name: set_active
methods.description: Activate/deactivate the tween. You can use this for pausing animations, though [method stop_all] and [method resume_all] might be more fit for this.

methods.name: set_repeat
methods.description: Make the tween repeat after all tweens have finished.

methods.name: set_speed_scale
methods.description: Set the speed multiplier of the tween. Set it to 1 for normal speed, 2 for two times nromal speed, and 0.5 for half of the normal speed. Setting it to 0 would pause the animation, but you might consider using [method set_active] or [method stop_all] and [method resume_all] for this.

methods.name: set_tween_process_mode
methods.description: Set whether the Tween uses [code]_process[/code] or [code]_physics_process[/code] (accepts TWEEN_PROCESS_IDLE and TWEEN_PROCESS_PHYSICS constants, respectively).

methods.name: start
methods.description: Start the tween node. You can define tweens both before and after this.

methods.name: stop
methods.description: Stop animating a tween, given its object and property/method pair. Passing empty String as key will stop all tweens for given object.

methods.name: stop_all
methods.description: Stop animating all tweens.

methods.name: targeting_method
methods.description:
Animate [code]method[/code] of [code]object[/code] from the value returned by [code]initial.initial_method[/code] to [code]final_val[/code] for [code]duration[/code] seconds, [code]delay[/code] seconds later. Methods are animated by calling them with consecutive values.
				[code]trans_type[/code] accepts TRANS_* constants, and is the way the animation is interpolated, while [code]ease_type[/code] accepts EASE_* constants, and controls the place of the interpolation (the beginning, the end, or both). You can read more about them in the class description.

methods.name: targeting_property
methods.description:
Animate [code]property[/code] of [code]object[/code] from the current value of the [code]initial_val[/code] property of [code]initial[/code] to [code]final_val[/code] for [code]duration[/code] seconds, [code]delay[/code] seconds later.
				[code]trans_type[/code] accepts TRANS_* constants, and is the way the animation is interpolated, while [code]ease_type[/code] accepts EASE_* constants, and controls the place of the interpolation (the beginning, the end, or both). You can read more about them in the class description.

methods.name: tell
methods.description: Returns the current time of the tween.

signals.name: tween_completed
signals.description: This signal is emitted when a tween ends.

signals.name: tween_started
signals.description: This signal is emitted when a tween starts.

signals.name: tween_step
signals.description: This signal is emitted each step of the tweening.

constants.name: TWEEN_PROCESS_PHYSICS
constants.description: The [Tween] should use [code]_physics_process[/code] for timekeeping when this is enabled.

constants.name: TWEEN_PROCESS_IDLE
constants.description: The [Tween] should use [code]_process[/code] for timekeeping when this is enabled (default).

constants.name: TRANS_LINEAR
constants.description: Means that the animation is interpolated linearly.

constants.name: TRANS_SINE
constants.description: Means that the animation is interpolated using a sine wave.

constants.name: TRANS_QUINT
constants.description: Means that the animation is interpolated with a quinary (to the power of 5) function.

constants.name: TRANS_QUART
constants.description: Means that the animation is interpolated with a quartic (to the power of 4) function.

constants.name: TRANS_QUAD
constants.description: Means that the animation is interpolated with a quadratic (to the power of 2) function.

constants.name: TRANS_EXPO
constants.description: Means that the animation is interpolated with an exponential (some number to the power of x) function.

constants.name: TRANS_ELASTIC
constants.description: Means that the animation is interpolated with elasticity, wiggling around the edges.

constants.name: TRANS_CUBIC
constants.description: Means that the animation is interpolated with a cubic (to the power of 3) function.

constants.name: TRANS_CIRC
constants.description: Means that the animation is interpolated with a function using square roots.

constants.name: TRANS_BOUNCE
constants.description: Means that the animation is interpolated by bouncing at, but never surpassing, the end.

constants.name: TRANS_BACK
constants.description: Means that the animation is interpolated backing out at edges.

constants.name: EASE_IN
constants.description: Signifies that the interpolation should be focused in the beginning.

constants.name: EASE_OUT
constants.description: Signifies that the interpolation should be focused in the end.

constants.name: EASE_IN_OUT
constants.description: Signifies that the interpolation should be focused in both ends.

constants.name: EASE_OUT_IN
constants.description: Signifies that the interpolation should be focused in both ends, but they should be switched (a bit hard to explain, try it for yourself to be sure).

Sprite3D.name: Sprite3D
Sprite3D.description: A node that displays a 2D texture in a 3D environment. The texture displayed can be a region from a larger atlas texture, or a frame from a sprite sheet animation.

signals.name: frame_changed
signals.description: Emitted when the [member frame] changes.

properties.name: frame
properties.description: Current frame to display from sprite sheet. [member vframes] or [member hframes] must be greater than 1.

properties.name: hframes
properties.description: The number of columns in the sprite sheet.

properties.name: region_enabled
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] texture will be cut from a larger atlas texture. See [member region_rect]. Default value: [code]false[/code].

properties.name: region_rect
properties.description: The region of the atlas texture to display. [member region_enabled] must be [code]true[/code].

properties.name: texture
properties.description: [Texture] object to draw.

properties.name: vframes
properties.description: The number of rows in the sprite sheet.

AudioStreamPlayer3D.name: AudioStreamPlayer3D
AudioStreamPlayer3D.description: Plays a sound effect with directed sound effects, dampens with distance if needed, generates effect of hearable position in space.

methods.name: get_playback_position
methods.description: Returns the position in the [AudioStream].

methods.name: play
methods.description: Plays the audio from the given position 'from_position', in seconds.

methods.name: seek
methods.description: Sets the position from which audio will be played, in seconds.

methods.name: stop
methods.description: Stops the audio.

signals.name: finished
signals.description: Fires when the audio stops playing.

constants.name: ATTENUATION_INVERSE_DISTANCE
constants.description: Linear dampening of loudness according to distance.

constants.name: ATTENUATION_INVERSE_SQUARE_DISTANCE
constants.description: Squared dampening of loudness according to distance.

constants.name: ATTENUATION_LOGARITHMIC
constants.description: Logarithmic dampening of loudness according to distance.

constants.name: OUT_OF_RANGE_MIX
constants.description: Mix this audio in, even when it's out of range.

constants.name: OUT_OF_RANGE_PAUSE
constants.description: Pause this audio when it gets out of range.

constants.name: DOPPLER_TRACKING_DISABLED
constants.description: Disables doppler tracking.

constants.name: DOPPLER_TRACKING_IDLE_STEP
constants.description: Executes doppler tracking in idle step.

constants.name: DOPPLER_TRACKING_PHYSICS_STEP
constants.description: Executes doppler tracking in physics step.

properties.name: area_mask
properties.description: Areas in which this sound plays.

properties.name: attenuation_filter_cutoff_hz
properties.description: Dampens audio above this frequency, in Hz.

properties.name: attenuation_filter_db
properties.description: Amount how much the filter affects the loudness, in dB.

properties.name: attenuation_model
properties.description: Decides if audio should get quieter with distance linearly, quadratically or logarithmically.

properties.name: autoplay
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] audio plays when added to scene tree. Default value: [code]false[/code].

properties.name: bus
properties.description: Bus on which this audio is playing.

properties.name: doppler_tracking
properties.description: Decides in which step the Doppler effect should be calculated.

properties.name: emission_angle_degrees
properties.description: The angle in which the audio reaches cameras undampened.

properties.name: emission_angle_enabled
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] the audio should be dampened according to the direction of the sound.

properties.name: emission_angle_filter_attenuation_db
properties.description: dampens audio if camera is outside of 'emission_angle_degrees' and 'emission_angle_enabled' is set by this factor, in dB.

properties.name: max_db
properties.description: Sets the absolute maximum of the soundlevel, in dB.

properties.name: max_distance
properties.description: Sets the distance from which the 'out_of_range_mode' takes effect. Has no effect if set to 0.

properties.name: out_of_range_mode
properties.description: Decides if audio should pause when source is outside of 'max_distance' range.

properties.name: playing
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], audio is playing.

properties.name: stream
properties.description: The [AudioStream] object to be played.

properties.name: unit_db
properties.description: Base sound level unaffected by dampening, in dB.

properties.name: unit_size
properties.description: Factor for the attenuation effect.

Gradient.name: Gradient
Gradient.description: Given a set of colors, this node will interpolate them in order, meaning, that if you have color 1, color 2 and color3, the ramp will interpolate (generate the colors between two colors) from color 1 to color 2 and from color 2 to color 3. Initially the ramp will have 2 colors (black and white), one (black) at ramp lower offset offset 0 and the other (white) at the ramp higher offset 1.

methods.name: add_point
methods.description: Adds the specified color to the end of the ramp, with the specified offset

methods.name: get_color
methods.description: Returns the color of the ramp color at index [i]point[/i]

methods.name: get_colors
methods.description: Returns the colors in the ramp

methods.name: get_offset
methods.description: Returns the offset of the ramp color at index [i]point[/i]

methods.name: get_offsets
methods.description: Returns the offsets for the colors in this ramp

methods.name: get_point_count
methods.description: Returns the number of colors in the ramp

methods.name: interpolate
methods.description: Returns the interpolated color specified by [i]offset[/i]

methods.name: remove_point
methods.description: Removes the color at the index [i]offset[/i]

methods.name: set_color
methods.description: Sets the color of the ramp color at index [i]point[/i]

methods.name: set_colors
methods.description: Sets the colors for the specified amount of elements. Calling this function with a different number of elements than previously defined causes the ramp to resize its colors and offsets array to accommodate the new elements.

methods.name: set_offset
methods.description: Sets the offset for the ramp color at index [i]point[/i]

methods.name: set_offsets
methods.description: Sets the offset for the specified amount of elements. Calling this function with a different number of elements than previously defined causes the ramp to resize its colors and offsets array to accommodate the new elements, all new colors will be black by default.

properties.name: colors
properties.description: Gradient's colors returned as a [PoolColorArray].

properties.name: offsets
properties.description: Gradient's offsets returned as a [PoolRealArray].

HSplitContainer.name: HSplitContainer
HSplitContainer.description: Horizontal split container. See [SplitContainer]. This goes from left to right.

ARVROrigin.name: ARVROrigin
ARVROrigin.description:
This is a special node within the AR/VR system that maps the physical location of the center of our tracking space to the virtual location within our game world.
		There should be only one of these nodes in your scene and you must have one. All the ARVRCamera, ARVRController and ARVRAnchor nodes should be direct children of this node for spatial tracking to work correctly.
		It is the position of this node that you update when you're character needs to move through your game world while we're not moving in the real world. Movement in the real world is always in relation to this origin point.
		So say that your character is driving a car, the ARVROrigin node should be a child node of this car. If you implement a teleport system to move your character, you change the position of this node. Etc.

methods.name: get_world_scale
methods.description: Get the world scale applied to our positioning.

methods.name: set_world_scale
methods.description:
Changes the world scaling factor.
				Most AR/VR platforms will assume a unit size of 1 unit in your game world = 1 meter in the real world. This scale allows you to adjust this to the unit system you use in your game. 
				Note that this method is a passthrough to the ARVRServer itself.

JSONParseResult.name: JSONParseResult
JSONParseResult.brief_description: Data class wrapper for decoded JSON.
JSONParseResult.description: Returned by [method JSON.parse], [JSONParseResult] contains decoded JSON or error information if JSON source not successfully parsed. You can check if JSON source was successfully parsed with [code]if json_result.error == 0[/code].

properties.name: error
properties.description: The error type if JSON source was not successfully parsed. See [@Global Scope]ERR_* constants.

properties.name: error_line
properties.description: The line number where the error occurred if JSON source was not successfully parsed.

properties.name: error_string
properties.description: The error message if JSON source was not successfully parsed. See [@Global Scope]ERR_* constants.

properties.name: result
properties.description:
A [Variant] containing the parsed JSON. Use typeof() to check if it is what you expect. For example, if JSON source starts with braces [code]{}[/code] a [Dictionary] will be returned, if JSON source starts with array braces [code][][/code] an [Array] will be returned.
			[i]Be aware that the JSON specification does not define integer or float types, but only a number type. Therefore, parsing a JSON text will convert all numerical values to float types.[/i]
			[codeblock]
			p = JSON.parse('["hello", "world", "!"]')
			if typeof(p) == TYPE_ARRAY:
				print(p[0]) # prints 'hello'
			else:
				print("unexpected results")
			[/codeblock]

SegmentShape2D.name: SegmentShape2D
SegmentShape2D.description: Segment shape for 2D collisions. Consists of two points, [code]a[/code] and [code]b[/code].

methods.name: get_a
methods.description: Return the first point's position.

methods.name: get_b
methods.description: Return the second point's position.

methods.name: set_a
methods.description: Set the first point's position.

methods.name: set_b
methods.description: Set the second point's position.

properties.name: a
properties.description: The segment's first point position.

properties.name: b
properties.description: The segment's second point position.

PhysicsBody.name: PhysicsBody
PhysicsBody.brief_description: Base class for all objects affected by physics in 3D space.
PhysicsBody.description: PhysicsBody is an abstract base class for implementing a physics body. All *Body types inherit from it.

methods.name: add_collision_exception_with
methods.description: Adds a body to the list of bodies that this body can't collide with.

methods.name: remove_collision_exception_with
methods.description: Removes a body from the list of bodies that this body can't collide with.

properties.name: collision_layer
properties.description:
The physics layers this area is in.
			Collidable objects can exist in any of 32 different layers. These layers work like a tagging system, and are not visual. A collidable can use these layers to select with which objects it can collide, using the collision_mask property.
			A contact is detected if object A is in any of the layers that object B scans, or object B is in any layer scanned by object A.

properties.name: collision_mask
properties.description: The physics layers this area can scan for collisions.

Camera.name: Camera
Camera.brief_description: Camera node, displays from a point of view.
Camera.description: Camera is a special node that displays what is visible from its current location. Cameras register themselves in the nearest [Viewport] node (when ascending the tree). Only one camera can be active per viewport. If no viewport is available ascending the tree, the Camera will register in the global viewport. In other words, a Camera just provides [i]3D[/i] display capabilities to a [Viewport], and, without one, a scene registered in that [Viewport] (or higher viewports) can't be displayed.

methods.name: clear_current
methods.description: If this is the current Camera, remove it from being current. If it is inside the node tree, request to make the next Camera current, if any.

methods.name: get_camera_transform
methods.description: Get the camera transform. Subclassed cameras (such as CharacterCamera) may provide different transforms than the [Node] transform.

methods.name: get_cull_mask
methods.description: Returns the culling mask, describing which 3D render layers are rendered by this Camera.

methods.name: get_environment
methods.description: Returns the [Environment] used by this Camera.

methods.name: get_fov
methods.description: Returns the [i]FOV[/i] Y angle in degrees (FOV means Field of View).

methods.name: get_h_offset
methods.description: Returns the horizontal (X) offset of the Camera viewport.

methods.name: get_keep_aspect_mode
methods.description: Returns the current mode for keeping the aspect ratio. See [code]KEEP_*[/code] constants.

methods.name: get_projection
methods.description: Returns the Camera's projection. See PROJECTION_* constants.

methods.name: get_v_offset
methods.description: Returns the vertical (Y) offset of the Camera viewport.

methods.name: get_zfar
methods.description: Returns the far clip plane in world space units.

methods.name: get_znear
methods.description: Returns the near clip plane in world space units.

methods.name: is_current
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the Camera is the current one in the [Viewport], or plans to become current (if outside the scene tree).

methods.name: is_position_behind
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the given position is behind the Camera.

methods.name: make_current
methods.description: Make this camera the current Camera for the [Viewport] (see class description). If the Camera Node is outside the scene tree, it will attempt to become current once it's added.

methods.name: project_position
methods.description: Returns how a 2D coordinate in the Viewport rectangle maps to a 3D point in worldspace.

methods.name: project_ray_normal
methods.description: Returns a normal vector in worldspace, that is the result of projecting a point on the [Viewport] rectangle by the camera projection. This is useful for casting rays in the form of (origin, normal) for object intersection or picking.

methods.name: project_ray_origin
methods.description: Returns a 3D position in worldspace, that is the result of projecting a point on the [Viewport] rectangle by the camera projection. This is useful for casting rays in the form of (origin, normal) for object intersection or picking.

methods.name: set_cull_mask
methods.description: Sets the cull mask, describing which 3D render layers are rendered by this Camera.

methods.name: set_doppler_tracking
methods.description: Changes Doppler effect tracking. See [code]DOPPLER_*[/code] constants.

methods.name: set_environment
methods.description: Sets the [Environment] to use for this Camera.

methods.name: set_h_offset
methods.description: Sets the horizontal (X) offset of the Camera viewport.

methods.name: set_keep_aspect_mode
methods.description: Sets the mode for keeping the aspect ratio. See [code]KEEP_*[/code] constants.

methods.name: set_orthogonal
methods.description: Set the camera projection to orthogonal mode, by specifying a width and the [i]near[/i] and [i]far[/i] clip planes in worldspace units. (As a hint, 2D games often use this projection, with values specified in pixels)

methods.name: set_perspective
methods.description: Set the camera projection to perspective mode, by specifying a [i]FOV[/i] Y angle in degrees (FOV means Field of View), and the [i]near[/i] and [i]far[/i] clip planes in worldspace units.

methods.name: set_v_offset
methods.description: Sets the vertical (Y) offset of the Camera viewport.

methods.name: unproject_position
methods.description: Returns how a 3D point in worldspace maps to a 2D coordinate in the [Viewport] rectangle.

constants.name: PROJECTION_PERSPECTIVE
constants.description: Perspective Projection (object's size on the screen becomes smaller when far away).

constants.name: PROJECTION_ORTHOGONAL
constants.description: Orthogonal Projection (objects remain the same size on the screen no matter how far away they are).

constants.name: KEEP_WIDTH
constants.description: Try to keep the aspect ratio when scaling the Camera's viewport to the screen. If not possible, preserve the viewport's width by changing the height. Height is [code]sizey[/code] for orthographic projection, [code]fovy[/code] for perspective projection.

constants.name: KEEP_HEIGHT
constants.description: Try to keep the aspect ratio when scaling the Camera's viewport to the screen. If not possible, preserve the viewport's height by changing the width. Width is [code]sizex[/code] for orthographic projection, [code]fovx[/code] for perspective projection.

constants.name: DOPPLER_TRACKING_DISABLED
constants.description: Disable Doppler effect simulation (default).

constants.name: DOPPLER_TRACKING_IDLE_STEP
constants.description: Simulate Doppler effect by tracking positions of objects that are changed in [code]_process[/code]. Changes in the relative velocity of this Camera compared to those objects affect how Audio is perceived (changing the Audio's [code]pitch shift[/code]).

constants.name: DOPPLER_TRACKING_PHYSICS_STEP
constants.description: Simulate Doppler effect by tracking positions of objects that are changed in [code]_physics_process[/code]. Changes in the relative velocity of this Camera compared to those objects affect how Audio is perceived (changing the Audio's [code]pitch shift[/code]).

TextureButton.name: TextureButton
TextureButton.brief_description: Texture-based button. Supports Pressed, Hover, Disabled and Focused states.
TextureButton.description:
[code]TextureButton[/code] has the same functionality as [Button], except it uses sprites instead of Godot's [Theme] resource. It is faster to create, but it doesn't support localization like more complex Controls.
		The Normal state's texture is required. Others are optional.

constants.name: STRETCH_SCALE
constants.description: Scale to fit the node's bounding rectangle.

constants.name: STRETCH_TILE
constants.description: Tile inside the node's bounding rectangle.

constants.name: STRETCH_KEEP
constants.description: The texture keeps its original size and stays in the bounding rectangle's top-left corner.

constants.name: STRETCH_KEEP_CENTERED
constants.description: The texture keeps its original size and stays centered in the node's bounding rectangle.

constants.name: STRETCH_KEEP_ASPECT
constants.description: Scale the texture to fit the node's bounding rectangle, but maintain the texture's aspect ratio.

constants.name: STRETCH_KEEP_ASPECT_CENTERED
constants.description: Scale the texture to fit the node's bounding rectangle, center it, and maintain its aspect ratio.

constants.name: STRETCH_KEEP_ASPECT_COVERED
constants.description: Scale the texture so that the shorter side fits the bounding rectangle. The other side clips to the node's limits.

properties.name: expand
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] the texture stretches to the edges of the node's bounding rectangle using the [member stretch_mode]. If [code]false[/code] the texture will not scale with the node. Default value: [code]false[/code].

properties.name: stretch_mode
properties.description: Controls the texture's behavior when you resize the node's bounding rectangle, [b]only if[/b] [member expand] is [code]true[/code]. Set it to one of the [code]STRETCH_*[/code] constants. See the constants to learn more.

properties.name: texture_click_mask
properties.description: Pure black and white [Bitmap] image to use for click detection. On the mask, white pixels represent the button's clickable area. Use it to create buttons with curved shapes.

properties.name: texture_disabled
properties.description: Texture to display when the node is disabled. See [member BaseButton.disabled].

properties.name: texture_focused
properties.description: Texture to display when the node has mouse or keyboard focus.

properties.name: texture_hover
properties.description: Texture to display when the mouse hovers the node.

properties.name: texture_normal
properties.description: Texture to display by default, when the node is [b]not[/b] in the disabled, focused, hover or pressed state.

properties.name: texture_pressed
properties.description: Texture to display on mouse down over the node, if the node has keyboard focus and the player presses the enter key or if the player presses the [member BaseButton.shortcut] key.

PoolColorArray.name: PoolColorArray
PoolColorArray.description: Array of Color, Contains colors. Optimized for memory usage, can't fragment the memory.

methods.name: PoolColorArray
methods.description: Create from a generic array.

methods.name: append
methods.description: Append an element at the end of the array (alias of [method push_back]).

methods.name: append_array
methods.description: Append a [PoolColorArray] at the end of this array.

methods.name: insert
methods.description: Insert a new element at a given position in the array. The position must be valid, or at the end of the array (pos==size()).

methods.name: invert
methods.description: Reverse the order of the elements in the array (so first element will now be the last).

methods.name: push_back
