GraphEdit.name: GraphEdit
GraphEdit.brief_description: GraphEdit is an area capable of showing various GraphNodes. It manages connection events between them.
GraphEdit.description:
GraphEdit manages the showing of GraphNodes it contains, as well as connections and disconnections between them. Signals are sent for each of these two events. Disconnection between GraphNodes slots is disabled by default.
		It is greatly advised to enable low processor usage mode (see [method OS.set_low_processor_usage_mode]) when using GraphEdits.

methods.name: connect_node
methods.description: Create a connection between 'from_port' slot of 'from' GraphNode and 'to_port' slot of 'to' GraphNode. If the connection already exists, no connection is created.

methods.name: disconnect_node
methods.description: Remove the connection between 'from_port' slot of 'from' GraphNode and 'to_port' slot of 'to' GraphNode, if connection exists.

methods.name: get_connection_list
methods.description: Return an Array containing the list of connections. A connection consists in a structure of the form {from_slot: 0, from: "GraphNode name 0", to_slot: 1, to: "GraphNode name 1" }

methods.name: get_scroll_ofs
methods.description: Return the scroll offset.

methods.name: get_zoom
methods.description: Return the current zoom value.

methods.name: is_node_connected
methods.description: Return true if the 'from_port' slot of 'from' GraphNode is connected to the 'to_port' slot of 'to' GraphNode.

methods.name: is_right_disconnects_enabled
methods.description: Return true is the disconnection of connections is enable in the visual GraphEdit. False otherwise.

methods.name: set_right_disconnects
methods.description: Enable the disconnection of existing connections in the visual GraphEdit by left-clicking a connection and releasing into the void.

methods.name: set_zoom
methods.description: Set the zoom value of the GraphEdit. Zoom value is between [0.01; 1.728].

signals.name: _begin_node_move
signals.description: Signal sent at the beginning of a GraphNode movement.

signals.name: _end_node_move
signals.description: Signal sent at the end of a GraphNode movement.

signals.name: connection_request
signals.description: Signal sent to the GraphEdit when the connection between 'from_slot' slot of 'from' GraphNode and 'to_slot' slot of 'to' GraphNode is attempted to be created.

signals.name: delete_nodes_request
signals.description: Signal sent when a GraphNode is attempted to be removed from the GraphEdit.

signals.name: disconnection_request
signals.description: Signal sent to the GraphEdit when the connection between 'from_slot' slot of 'from' GraphNode and 'to_slot' slot of 'to' GraphNode is attempted to be removed.

signals.name: duplicate_nodes_request
signals.description: Signal sent when a GraphNode is attempted to be duplicated in the GraphEdit.

signals.name: popup_request
signals.description: Signal sent when a popup is requested. Happens on right-clicking in the GraphEdit. 'p_position' is the position of the mouse pointer when the signal is sent.

Separator.description: Separator is a [Control] used for separating other controls. It's purely a visual decoration. Horizontal ([HSeparator]) and Vertical ([VSeparator]) versions are available.

MobileVRInterface.name: MobileVRInterface
MobileVRInterface.description:
This is a generic mobile VR implementation where you need to provide details about the phone and HMD used. It does not rely on any existing framework. This is the most basic interface we have. For the best effect you do need a mobile phone with a gyroscope and accelerometer.
		Note that even though there is no positional tracking the camera will assume the headset is at a height of 1.85 meters.

properties.description: The oversample setting. Because of the lens distortion we have to render our buffers at a higher resolution then the screen can natively handle. A value between 1.5 and 2.0 often provides good results but at the cost of performance.

NodePath.name: NodePath
NodePath.description:
A pre-parsed relative or absolute path in a scene tree, for use with [method Node.get_node] and similar functions. It can reference a node, a resource within a node, or a property of a node or resource. For instance, [code]"Path2D/PathFollow2D/Sprite:texture:size"[/code] would refer to the size property of the texture resource on the node named "Sprite" which is a child of the other named nodes in the path. Note that if you want to get a resource, you must end the path with a colon, otherwise the last element will be used as a property name.
		You will usually just pass a string to [method Node.get_node] and it will be automatically converted, but you may occasionally want to parse a path ahead of time with [NodePath] or the literal syntax [code]@"path"[/code]. Exporting a [NodePath] variable will give you a node selection widget in the properties panel of the editor, which can often be useful.
		A [NodePath] is made up of a list of node names, a list of "subnode" (resource) names, and the name of a property in the final node or resource.

methods.name: NodePath
methods.description: Create a NodePath from a string, e.g. "Path2D/PathFollow2D/Sprite:texture:size". A path is absolute if it starts with a slash. Absolute paths are only valid in the global scene tree, not within individual scenes. In a relative path, [code]"."[/code] and [code]".."[/code] indicate the current node and its parent.

methods.name: get_name
methods.description: Get the node name indicated by [code]idx[/code] (0 to [method get_name_count])

methods.name: get_name_count
methods.description: Get the number of node names which make up the path.

methods.name: get_property
methods.description: Get the path's property name, or an empty string if the path doesn't have a property.

methods.name: get_subname
methods.description: Get the resource name indicated by [code]idx[/code] (0 to [method get_subname_count])

methods.name: get_subname_count
methods.description: Get the number of resource names in the path.

methods.name: is_absolute
methods.description: Return true if the node path is absolute (not relative).

methods.name: is_empty
methods.description: Return true if the node path is empty.

KinematicBody.name: KinematicBody
KinematicBody.description:
Kinematic bodies are special types of bodies that are meant to be user-controlled. They are not affected by physics at all (to other types of bodies, such a character or a rigid body, these are the same as a static body). They have however, two main uses:
		Simulated Motion: When these bodies are moved manually, either from code or from an AnimationPlayer (with process mode set to fixed), the physics will automatically compute an estimate of their linear and angular velocity. This makes them very useful for moving platforms or other AnimationPlayer-controlled objects (like a door, a bridge that opens, etc).
		Kinematic Characters: KinematicBody also has an API for moving objects (the [method move_and_collide] and [method move_and_slide] methods) while performing collision tests. This makes them really useful to implement characters that collide against a world, but that don't require advanced physics.

methods.name: get_floor_velocity
methods.description: Returns the velocity of the floor. Only updates when calling [method move_and_slide].

methods.name: get_slide_collision
methods.description: Returns a [KinematicCollision], which contains information about a collision that occured during the last [method move_and_slide] call. Since the body can collide several times in a single call to [method move_and_slide], you must specify the index of the collision in the range 0 to ([method get_slide_count]()-1).

methods.name: get_slide_count
methods.description: Returns the number of times the body collided and changed direction during the last call to [method move_and_slide].

methods.name: is_on_ceiling
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the body is on the ceiling. Only updates when calling [method move_and_slide].

methods.name: is_on_floor
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the body is on the floor. Only updates when calling [method move_and_slide].

methods.name: is_on_wall
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the body is on a wall. Only updates when calling [method move_and_slide].

methods.name: move_and_collide
methods.description: Moves the body along the vector [code]rel_vec[/code]. The body will stop if it collides. Returns a [KinematicCollision], which contains information about the collision.

methods.name: move_and_slide
methods.description:
Moves the body along a vector. If the body collides with another, it will slide along the other body rather than stop immediately. If the other body is a [KinematicBody] or [RigidBody], it will also be affected by the motion of the other body. You can use this to make moving or rotating platforms, or to make nodes push other nodes.
				[code]linear_velocity[/code] is a value in pixels per second. Unlike in for example [method move_and_collide], you should [i]not[/i] multiply it with [code]delta[/code]  this is done by the method.
				[code]floor_normal[/code] is the up direction, used to determine what is a wall and what is a floor or a ceiling. If set to the default value of [code]Vector2(0, 0)[/code], everything is considered a wall. This is useful for topdown games.
				If the body is standing on a slope and the horizontal speed (relative to the floor's speed) goes below [code]slope_stop_min_velocity[/code], the body will stop completely. This prevents the body from sliding down slopes when you include gravity in [code]linear_velocity[/code]. When set to lower values, the body will not be able to stand still on steep slopes.
				If the body collides, it will change direction a maximum of [code]max_bounces[/code] times before it stops.
				[code]floor_max_angle[/code] is the maximum angle (in radians) where a slope is still considered a floor (or a ceiling), rather than a wall. The default value equals 45 degrees.
				Returns the movement that remained when the body stopped. To get more detailed information about collisions that occured, use [method get_slide_collision].

methods.name: test_move
methods.description: Checks for collisions without moving the body. Virtually sets the node's position, scale and rotation to that of the given [Transform], then tries to move the body along the vector [code]rel_vec[/code]. Returns [code]true[/code] if a collision would occur.

properties.name: collision/safe_margin
properties.description: If the body is at least this close to another body, this body will consider them to be colliding.

ARVRServer.name: ARVRServer
ARVRServer.description: The AR/VR Server is the heart of our AR/VR solution and handles all the processing.

methods.name: add_interface
methods.description: Mostly exposed for GDNative based interfaces, this is called to register an available interface with the AR/VR server.

methods.name: center_on_hmd
methods.description:
This is a really important function to understand correctly. AR and VR platforms all handle positioning slightly differently.
				For platforms that do not offer spatial tracking our origin point (0,0,0) is the location of our HMD but you have little control over the direction the player is facing in the real world.
				For platforms that do offer spatial tracking our origin point depends very much on the system. For OpenVR our origin point is usually the center of the tracking space, on the ground. For other platforms its often the location of the tracking camera.
				This method allows you to center our tracker on the location of the HMD, it will take the current location of the HMD and use that to adjust all our tracking data in essence realigning the real world to your players current position in your game world.
				For this method to produce usable results tracking information should be available and this often takes a few frames after starting your game.
				You should call this method after a few seconds have passed, when the user requests a realignment of the display holding a designated button on a controller for a short period of time, and when implementing a teleport mechanism.

methods.name: find_interface
methods.description: Find an interface by its name. Say that you're making a game that uses specific capabilities of an AR/VR platform you can find the interface for that platform by name and initialize it.

methods.name: get_interface
methods.description: Get the interface registered at a given index in our list of interfaces.

methods.name: get_interface_count
methods.description: Get the number of interfaces currently registered with the AR/VR server. If you're game supports multiple AR/VR platforms you can look throught the available interface and either present the user with a selection or simply try an initialize each interface and use the first one that returns true.

methods.name: get_reference_frame
methods.description: Gets our reference frame transform, mostly used internally and exposed for GDNative build interfaces.

methods.name: get_tracker
methods.description: Get the positional tracker at the given ID.

methods.name: get_tracker_count
methods.description: Get the number of trackers currently registered.

methods.name: get_world_scale
methods.description: Returns our world scale (see ARVROrigin for more information).

methods.name: remove_interface
methods.description: Removes a registered interface, again exposed mostly for GDNative based interfaces.

methods.name: set_primary_interface
methods.description: Changes the primary interface to the specified interface. Again mostly exposed for GDNative interfaces.

methods.name: set_world_scale
methods.description: Changing the world scale, see the ARVROrigin documentation for more information.

signals.name: interface_added
signals.description: Signal send when a new interface has been added.

signals.name: interface_removed
signals.description: Signal send when an interface is removed.

signals.name: tracker_added
signals.description: Signal send when a new tracker has been added. If you don't use a fixed number of controllers or if you're using ARVRAnchors for an AR solution it is important to react to this signal and add the appropriate ARVRController or ARVRAnchor node related to this new tracker.

signals.name: tracker_removed
signals.description: Signal send when a tracker is removed, you should remove any ARVRController or ARVRAnchor points if applicable. This is not mandatory, the nodes simply become inactive and will be made active again when a new tracker becomes available (i.e. a new controller is switched on that takes the place of the previous one).

constants.name: TRACKER_CONTROLLER
constants.description: Our tracker tracks the location of a controller.

constants.name: TRACKER_BASESTATION
constants.description: Our tracker tracks the location of a base station.

constants.name: TRACKER_ANCHOR
constants.description: Our tracker tracks the location and size of an AR anchor.

constants.name: TRACKER_UNKNOWN
constants.description: Used internally if we haven't set the tracker type yet.

constants.name: TRACKER_ANY_KNOWN
constants.description: Used internally to filter trackers of any known type.

constants.name: TRACKER_ANY
constants.description: Used internally to select all trackers.

PacketPeer.name: PacketPeer
PacketPeer.brief_description: Abstraction and base class for packet-based protocols.
PacketPeer.description: PacketPeer is an abstraction and base class for packet-based protocols (such as UDP). It provides an API for sending and receiving packets both as raw data or variables. This makes it easy to transfer data over a protocol, without having to encode data as low level bytes or having to worry about network ordering.

methods.name: get_available_packet_count
methods.description: Return the number of packets currently available in the ring-buffer.

methods.name: get_packet
methods.description: Get a raw packet.

methods.name: get_packet_error
methods.description: Return the error state of the last packet received (via [method get_packet] and [method get_var]).

methods.name: get_var
methods.description: Get a Variant.

methods.name: put_packet
methods.description: Send a raw packet.

methods.name: put_var
methods.description: Send a Variant as a packet.

Light2D.name: Light2D
Light2D.description: Casts light in a 2D environment. Light is defined by a (usually grayscale) texture, a color, an energy value, a mode (see constants), and various other parameters (range and shadows-related). Note that Light2D can be used as a mask.

methods.name: get_color
methods.description: Return the color of the Light2D.

methods.name: get_energy
methods.description: Return the energy value of the Light2D.

methods.name: get_height

methods.name: get_layer_range_max

methods.name: get_layer_range_min
methods.description: Get the minimum layer value of objects of the scene that are affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: get_mode

methods.name: get_shadow_buffer_size

methods.name: get_shadow_color

methods.name: get_texture

methods.name: get_texture_offset

methods.name: get_texture_scale

methods.name: get_z_range_max
methods.description: Get the maximum Z value that objects of the scene can be in order to be affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: get_z_range_min
methods.description: Get the minimum Z value that objects of the scene have to be in order to be affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: is_enabled
methods.description: Return true if the Light2D is enabled, false if it is not.

methods.name: is_shadow_enabled
methods.description: Return true if shadow casting is enabled for this Light2D, else return false.

methods.name: set_color
methods.description: Set the color of the Light2D.

methods.name: set_enabled
methods.description: Switches the Light2D on or off, depending on the 'enabled' parameter.

methods.name: set_energy
methods.description: Set the energy value of the Light2D. The bigger the value, the stronger the light.

methods.name: set_height
methods.description: Set the height of the Light2D. Used with 2D normalmapping.

methods.name: set_item_cull_mask
methods.description: Set the item mask of the Light2D to 'item_mask' value.

methods.name: set_item_shadow_cull_mask
methods.description: Set the item shadow mask to 'item_shadow_mask' value.

methods.name: set_layer_range_max
methods.description: Set the maximum layer value of objects of the scene that are affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: set_layer_range_min
methods.description: Set the minimum layer value of objects of the scene that are affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: set_mode
methods.description: Set the behaviour mode of the Light2D. Use constants defined in the constants section.

methods.name: set_shadow_buffer_size
methods.description: Set the shadow buffer size.

methods.name: set_shadow_color
methods.description: Set the color of casted shadows for this Light2D.

methods.name: set_shadow_enabled
methods.description: Enable or disable shadows casting from this Light2D according to the 'enabled' parameter.

methods.name: set_texture
methods.description: Set the texture of the Light2D.

methods.name: set_texture_offset
methods.description: Set the offset of the light texture.

methods.name: set_texture_scale
methods.description: Set the scale value of the light texture.

methods.name: set_z_range_max
methods.description: Set the maximum Z value that objects of the scene can be in order to be affected by the Light2D.

methods.name: set_z_range_min
methods.description: Set the minimum Z value that objects of the scene have to be in order to be affected by the Light2D.

constants.name: MODE_ADD
constants.description: Adds the value of pixels corresponding to the Light2D to the values of pixels under it. This is the common behaviour of a light.

constants.name: MODE_SUB
constants.description: Subtracts the value of pixels corresponding to the Light2D to the values of pixels under it, resulting in inversed light effect.

constants.name: MODE_MIX
constants.description: Mix the value of pixels corresponding to the Light2D to the values of pixels under it by linear interpolation.

constants.name: MODE_MASK
constants.description: The light texture of the Light2D is used as a mask, hiding or revealing parts of the screen underneath depending on the value of each pixel of the light (mask) texture.

constants.name: SHADOW_FILTER_NONE
constants.description: No filter applies to the shadow map. See [method shadow_filter].

constants.name: SHADOW_FILTER_PCF3
constants.description: Percentage closer filtering (3 samples) applies to the shadow map. See [method shadow_filter].

constants.name: SHADOW_FILTER_PCF5
constants.description: Percentage closer filtering (5 samples) applies to the shadow map. See [method shadow_filter].

constants.name: SHADOW_FILTER_PCF7
constants.description: Percentage closer filtering (7 samples) applies to the shadow map. See [method shadow_filter].

constants.name: SHADOW_FILTER_PCF9
constants.description: Percentage closer filtering (9 samples) applies to the shadow map. See [method shadow_filter].

constants.name: SHADOW_FILTER_PCF13
constants.description: Percentage closer filtering (13 samples) applies to the shadow map. See [method shadow_filter].

properties.name: color
properties.description: The Light2D's [Color].

properties.name: editor_only
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] Light2D will only appear when editing the scene. Default value: [code]false[/code].

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] Light2D will emit light. Default value: [code]true[/code].

properties.name: energy
properties.description: The Light2D's energy value. The larger the value, the stronger the light.

properties.name: mode
properties.description: The Light2D's mode. See MODE_* constants for values.

properties.name: offset
properties.description: The offset of the Light2D's [code]texture[/code].

properties.name: range_height
properties.description: The height of the Light2D. Used with 2D normal mapping.

properties.name: range_item_cull_mask
properties.description: The layer mask. Only objects with a matching mask will be affected by the Light2D.

properties.name: range_layer_max
properties.description: Maximum layer value of objects that are affected by the Light2D. Default value: [code]0[/code].

properties.name: range_layer_min
properties.description: Minimum layer value of objects that are affected by the Light2D. Default value: [code]0[/code].

properties.name: range_z_max
properties.description: Maximum [code]Z[/code] value of objects that are affected by the Light2D. Default value: [code]1024[/code].

properties.name: range_z_min
properties.description: Minimum [code]z[/code] value of objects that are affected by the Light2D. Default value: [code]-1024[/code].

properties.name: shadow_buffer_size
properties.description: Shadow buffer size. Default value: [code]2048[/code].

properties.name: shadow_color
properties.description: [Color] of shadows cast by the Light2D.

properties.name: shadow_enabled
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] the Light2D will cast shadows. Default value: [code]false[/code].

properties.name: shadow_filter
properties.description: Shadow filter type. Use SHADOW_FILTER_* constants to set [code]shadow_filter[/code]. Default value: [code]None[/code].

properties.name: shadow_filter_smooth
properties.description: Smoothing value for shadows.

properties.name: shadow_gradient_length
properties.description: Smooth shadow gradient length.

properties.name: shadow_item_cull_mask
properties.description: The shadow mask. Used with [LightOccluder2D] to cast shadows. Only occluders with a matching shadow mask will cast shadows.

properties.name: texture
properties.description: [Texture] used for the Light2D's appearance.

properties.name: texture_scale
properties.description: The [code]texture[/code]'s scale factor.

GeometryInstance.name: GeometryInstance
GeometryInstance.brief_description: Base node for geometry based visual instances.
GeometryInstance.description: Base node for geometry based visual instances. Shares some common functionality like visibility and custom materials.

methods.name: get_material_override
methods.description: Return the material override for the whole geometry.

methods.name: set_material_override
methods.description: Set the material override for the whole geometry.

Area2D.name: Area2D
Area2D.brief_description: 2D area for detection and 2D physics influence.
Area2D.description: 2D area that detects [CollisionObject2D] nodes overlapping, entering, or exiting. Can also alter or override local physics parameters (gravity, damping).

methods.name: get_angular_damp
methods.description: Return the angular damp rate.

methods.name: get_collision_layer
methods.description: Return the physics layer this area is in.

methods.name: get_collision_layer_bit
methods.description: Return an individual bit on the layer mask. Describes whether other areas will collide with this one on the given layer.

methods.name: get_collision_mask
methods.description: Return the physics layers this area will scan to determine collisions.

methods.name: get_collision_mask_bit
methods.description: Return an individual bit on the collision mask. Describes whether this area will collide with others on the given layer.

methods.name: get_gravity
methods.description: Return the gravity intensity.

methods.name: get_gravity_distance_scale
methods.description: Return the falloff factor for point gravity.

methods.name: get_gravity_vector
methods.description: Return the gravity vector. If gravity is a point (see [method is_gravity_a_point]), this will be the attraction center.

methods.name: get_linear_damp
methods.description: Return the linear damp rate.

methods.name: get_overlapping_areas
methods.description: Returns a list of intersecting [Area2D]\ s.

methods.name: get_overlapping_bodies
methods.description: Returns a list of intersecting [PhysicsBody2D]\ s.

methods.name: get_priority
methods.description: Return the processing order of this area.

methods.name: get_space_override_mode
methods.description: Return the space override mode.

methods.name: is_gravity_a_point
methods.description: Return whether gravity is a point. A point gravity will attract objects towards it, as opposed to a gravity vector, which moves them in a given direction.

methods.name: is_monitorable
methods.description: Return whether this area can be detected by other, monitoring, areas.

methods.name: is_monitoring
methods.description: Return whether this area detects bodies/areas entering/exiting it.

methods.name: overlaps_area
methods.description: If [code]true[/code] the given area overlaps the Area2D.

methods.name: overlaps_body
methods.description: If [code]true[/code] the given body overlaps the Area2D.

methods.name: set_angular_damp
methods.description:
Set the rate at which objects stop spinning in this area, if there are not any other forces making it spin. The value is a fraction of its current speed, lost per second. Thus, a value of 1.0 should mean stopping immediately, and 0.0 means the object never stops.
				In practice, as the fraction of speed lost gets smaller with each frame, a value of 1.0 does not mean the object will stop in exactly one second. Only when the physics calculations are done at 1 frame per second, it does stop in a second.

methods.name: set_collision_layer
methods.description:
Set the physics layers this area is in.
				Collidable objects can exist in any of 32 different layers. These layers are not visual, but more of a tagging system instead. A collidable can use these layers/tags to select with which objects it can collide, using [method set_collision_mask].
				A contact is detected if object A is in any of the layers that object B scans, or object B is in any layer scanned by object A.

methods.name: set_collision_layer_bit
methods.description: Set/clear individual bits on the layer mask. This makes getting an area in/out of only one layer easier.

methods.name: set_collision_mask
methods.description: Set the physics layers this area can scan for collisions.

methods.name: set_collision_mask_bit
methods.description: Set/clear individual bits on the collision mask. This makes selecting the areas scanned easier.

methods.name: set_gravity
methods.description:
Set the gravity intensity. This is useful to alter the force of gravity without altering its direction.
				This value multiplies the gravity vector, whether it is the given vector ([method set_gravity_vector]), or a calculated one (when using a center of gravity).

methods.name: set_gravity_distance_scale
methods.description: Set the falloff factor for point gravity. The greater this value is, the faster the strength of gravity decreases with the square of distance.

methods.name: set_gravity_is_point
methods.description: When overriding space parameters, this method sets whether this area has a center of gravity. To set/get the location of the center of gravity, use [method set_gravity_vector]/[method get_gravity_vector].

methods.name: set_gravity_vector
methods.description:
Set the gravity vector. This vector does not have to be normalized.
				If gravity is a point (see [method is_gravity_a_point]), this will be the attraction center.

methods.name: set_linear_damp
methods.description:
Set the rate at which objects stop moving in this area, if there are not any other forces moving it. The value is a fraction of its current speed, lost per second. Thus, a value of 1.0 should mean stopping immediately, and 0.0 means the object never stops.
				In practice, as the fraction of speed lost gets smaller with each frame, a value of 1.0 does not mean the object will stop in exactly one second. Only when the physics calculations are done at 1 frame per second, it does stop in a second.

methods.name: set_monitorable
methods.description: Set whether this area can be detected by other, monitoring, areas. Only areas need to be marked as monitorable. Bodies are always so.

methods.name: set_monitoring
methods.description: Set whether this area can detect bodies/areas entering/exiting it.

methods.name: set_priority
methods.description:
Set the order in which the area is processed. Greater values mean the area gets processed first. This is useful for areas which have a space override different from AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_DISABLED or AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_COMBINE, as they replace values, and are thus order-dependent.
				Areas with the same priority value get evaluated in an unpredictable order, and should be differentiated if evaluation order is to be important.

methods.name: set_space_override_mode
methods.description:
Set the space override mode. This mode controls how an area affects gravity and damp.
				AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_DISABLED: This area does not affect gravity/damp. These are generally areas that exist only to detect collisions, and objects entering or exiting them.
				AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_COMBINE: This area adds its gravity/damp values to whatever has been calculated so far. This way, many overlapping areas can combine their physics to make interesting effects.
				AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_COMBINE_REPLACE: This area adds its gravity/damp values to whatever has been calculated so far. Then stops taking into account the rest of the areas, even the default one.
				AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_REPLACE: This area replaces any gravity/damp, even the default one, and stops taking into account the rest of the areas.
				AREA_SPACE_OVERRIDE_REPLACE_COMBINE: This area replaces any gravity/damp calculated so far, but keeps calculating the rest of the areas, down to the default one.

signals.name: area_entered
signals.description: Emitted when another area enters.

signals.name: area_exited
signals.description: Emitted when another area exits.

signals.name: area_shape_entered
signals.description: Emitted when another area enters, reporting which shapes overlapped.

signals.name: area_shape_exited
signals.description: Emitted when another area exits, reporting which shapes were overlapping.

signals.name: body_entered
signals.description: Emitted when a [PhysicsBody2D] object enters.

signals.name: body_exited
signals.description: Emitted when a [PhysicsBody2D] object exits.

signals.name: body_shape_entered
signals.description: Emitted when a [PhysicsBody2D] object enters, reporting which shapes overlapped.

signals.name: body_shape_exited
signals.description: Emitted when a [PhysicsBody2D] object exits, reporting which shapes were overlapping.

constants.name: SPACE_OVERRIDE_DISABLED
constants.description: This area does not affect gravity/damping.

constants.name: SPACE_OVERRIDE_COMBINE
constants.description: This area adds its gravity/damping values to whatever has been calculated so far (in [code]priority[/code] order).

constants.name: SPACE_OVERRIDE_COMBINE_REPLACE
constants.description: This area adds its gravity/damping values to whatever has been calculated so far (in [code]priority[/code] order), ignoring any lower priority areas.

constants.name: SPACE_OVERRIDE_REPLACE
constants.description: This area replaces any gravity/damping, even the defaults, ignoring any lower priority areas.

constants.name: SPACE_OVERRIDE_REPLACE_COMBINE
constants.description: This area replaces any gravity/damping calculated so far (in [code]priority[/code] order), but keeps calculating the rest of the areas.

properties.name: angular_damp
properties.description: The rate at which objects stop spinning in this area. Represents the angular velocity lost per second. Values range from [code]0[/code] (no damping) to [code]1[/code] (full damping).

properties.name: audio_bus_name
properties.description: The name of the area's audio bus.

properties.name: audio_bus_override
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] the area's audio bus overrides the default audio bus. Default value: [code]false[/code].

properties.name: collision_layer
properties.description: The area's physics layer(s). Collidable objects can exist in any of 32 different layers. A contact is detected if object A is in any of the layers that object B scans, or object B is in any layers that object A scans. See also [code]collision_mask[/code].

properties.name: collision_mask
properties.description: The physics layers this area scans to determine collision detection.

properties.name: gravity
properties.description: The area's gravity intensity (ranges from -1024 to 1024). This value multiplies the gravity vector. This is useful to alter the force of gravity without altering its direction.

properties.name: gravity_distance_scale
properties.description: The falloff factor for point gravity. The greater the value, the faster gravity decreases with distance.

properties.name: gravity_point
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] gravity is calculated from a point (set via [code]gravity_vec[/code]). Also see [code]space_override[/code]. Default value: [code]false[/code].

properties.name: gravity_vec
properties.description: The area's gravity vector (not normalized). If gravity is a point (see [method is_gravity_a_point]), this will be the point of attraction.

properties.name: linear_damp
properties.description: The rate at which objects stop moving in this area. Represents the linear velocity lost per second. Values range from [code]0[/code] (no damping) to [code]1[/code] (full damping).

properties.name: monitorable
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] other monitoring areas can detect this area. Default value: [code]true[/code].

properties.name: monitoring
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] the area detects bodies or areas entering and exiting it. Default value: [code]true[/code].

properties.name: priority
properties.description: The area's priority. Higher priority areas are processed first. Default value: 0.

properties.name: space_override
properties.description: Override mode for gravity and damping calculations within this area. See the SPACE_OVERRIDE_* constants for values.

CanvasItem.name: CanvasItem
CanvasItem.description:
Base class of anything 2D. Canvas items are laid out in a tree and children inherit and extend the transform of their parent. CanvasItem is extended by [Control], for anything GUI related, and by [Node2D] for anything 2D engine related.
		Any CanvasItem can draw. For this, the "update" function must be called, then NOTIFICATION_DRAW will be received on idle time to request redraw. Because of this, canvas items don't need to be redraw on every frame, improving the performance significantly. Several functions for drawing on the CanvasItem are provided (see draw_* functions). They can only be used inside the notification, signal or _draw() overrides function, though.
		Canvas items are draw in tree order. By default, children are on top of their parents so a root CanvasItem will be drawn behind everything (this can be changed per item though).
		Canvas items can also be hidden (hiding also their subtree). They provide many means for changing standard parameters such as opacity (for it and the subtree) and self opacity, blend mode.
		Ultimately, a transform notification can be requested, which will notify the node that its global position changed in case the parent tree changed.

methods.name: _draw
methods.description: Called (if exists) to draw the canvas item.

methods.name: draw_char
methods.description: Draw a string character using a custom font. Returns the advance, depending on the char width and kerning with an optional next char.

methods.name: draw_circle
methods.description: Draw a colored circle.

methods.name: draw_colored_polygon
methods.description: Draw a colored polygon of any amount of points, convex or concave.

methods.name: draw_line
methods.description: Draw a line from a 2D point to another, with a given color and width. It can be optionally antialiased.

methods.name: draw_polygon
methods.description: Draw a polygon of any amount of points, convex or concave.

methods.name: draw_primitive
methods.description: Draw a custom primitive, 1 point for a point, 2 points for a line, 3 points for a triangle and 4 points for a quad.

methods.name: draw_rect
methods.description: Draw a colored rectangle.

methods.name: draw_set_transform
methods.description: Set a custom transform for drawing. Anything drawn afterwards will be transformed by this.

methods.name: draw_string
methods.description: Draw a string using a custom font.

methods.name: draw_style_box
methods.description: Draw a styled rectangle.

methods.name: draw_texture
methods.description: Draw a texture at a given position.

methods.name: draw_texture_rect
methods.description: Draw a textured rectangle at a given position, optionally modulated by a color. Transpose swaps the x and y coordinates when reading the texture.

methods.name: draw_texture_rect_region
methods.description: Draw a textured rectangle region at a given position, optionally modulated by a color. Transpose swaps the x and y coordinates when reading the texture.

methods.name: edit_get_state
methods.description: Used for editing, returns an opaque value representing the transform state.

methods.name: edit_rotate
methods.description: Used for editing, handle rotation.

methods.name: edit_set_state
methods.description: Set the transform state of this CanvasItem. For [Node2D], this is an [Array] with (in order) a [Vector2] for position, a float for rotation (radians) and another [Vector2] for scale. For [Control] this is a [Rect2] with the position and size.

methods.name: get_canvas
methods.description: Return the [RID] of the [World2D] canvas where this item is in.

methods.name: get_canvas_item
methods.description: Return the canvas item RID used by [VisualServer] for this item.

methods.name: get_canvas_transform
methods.description: Get the transform matrix of this item's canvas.

methods.name: get_global_mouse_position
methods.description: Get the global position of the mouse.

methods.name: get_global_transform
methods.description: Get the global transform matrix of this item.

methods.name: get_global_transform_with_canvas
methods.description: Get the global transform matrix of this item in relation to the canvas.

methods.name: get_item_and_children_rect
methods.description: Get a [Rect2] with the boundaries of this item and its children.

methods.name: get_item_rect
methods.description: Return a rect containing the editable boundaries of the item.

methods.name: get_light_mask
methods.description: Get this item's light mask number.

methods.name: get_local_mouse_position
methods.description: Get the mouse position relative to this item's position.

methods.name: get_material
methods.description: Get the material of this item.

methods.name: get_modulate
methods.description: Get the modulate of the CanvasItem, which affects children items too.

methods.name: get_self_modulate
methods.description: Get the self-modulate of the CanvasItem.

methods.name: get_transform
methods.description: Get the transform matrix of this item.

methods.name: get_use_parent_material
methods.description: Get whether this item uses its parent's material.

methods.name: get_viewport_rect
methods.description: Get the viewport's boundaries as a [Rect2].

methods.name: get_viewport_transform
methods.description: Get this item's transform in relation to the viewport.

methods.name: get_world_2d
methods.description: Get the [World2D] where this item is in.

methods.name: hide
methods.description: Hide the CanvasItem currently visible.

methods.name: is_draw_behind_parent_enabled
methods.description: Return whether the item is drawn behind its parent.

methods.name: is_set_as_toplevel
methods.description: Return if set as toplevel. See [method set_as_toplevel].

methods.name: is_visible
methods.description: Return true if this CanvasItem is visible. It may be invisible because itself or a parent canvas item is hidden.

methods.name: set_as_toplevel
methods.description: Set as top level. This means that it will not inherit transform from parent canvas items.

methods.name: set_draw_behind_parent
methods.description: Set whether the canvas item is drawn behind its parent.

methods.name: set_light_mask
methods.description: Set the ligtht mask number of this item.

methods.name: set_material
methods.description: Set the material of this item.

methods.name: set_modulate
methods.description: Set the modulate of the CanvasItem. This [i]affects[/i] the modulation of children items.

methods.name: set_self_modulate
methods.description: Set the self-modulate of the CanvasItem. This does not affect the modulation of children items.

methods.name: set_use_parent_material
methods.description: Set whether or not this item should use its parent's material.

methods.name: set_visible
methods.description:
Set whether this item should be visible or not.
				Note that a hidden CanvasItem will make all children hidden too, so no matter what is set here this item won't be shown if its parent or grandparents nodes are hidden.

methods.name: show
methods.description: Show the CanvasItem currently hidden.

methods.name: update
methods.description: Queue the CanvasItem for update. [code]NOTIFICATION_DRAW[/code] will be called on idle time to request redraw.

signals.name: draw
signals.description: Emitted when the CanvasItem must redraw. This can only be connected realtime, as deferred will not allow drawing.

signals.name: hide
signals.description: Emitted when becoming hidden.

signals.name: item_rect_changed
signals.description: Emitted when the item rect has changed.

signals.name: visibility_changed
signals.description: Emitted when the visibility (hidden/visible) changes.

constants.name: BLEND_MODE_MIX
constants.description: Mix blending mode. Colors are assumed to be independent of the alpha (opacity) value.

constants.name: BLEND_MODE_ADD
constants.description: Additive blending mode.

constants.name: BLEND_MODE_SUB
constants.description: Subtractive blending mode.

constants.name: BLEND_MODE_MUL

constants.name: BLEND_MODE_PREMULT_ALPHA
constants.description: Mix blending mode. Colors are assumed to be premultiplied by the alpha (opacity) value.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_DRAW

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_VISIBILITY_CHANGED
constants.description: Canvas item visibility has changed.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_ENTER_CANVAS

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_EXIT_CANVAS

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_TRANSFORM_CHANGED

AudioEffectDelay.name: AudioEffectDelay
AudioEffectDelay.brief_description:
Adds a Delay audio effect to an Audio bus. Plays input signal back after a period of time.
		Two tap delay and feedback options.
AudioEffectDelay.description: Plays input signal back after a period of time. The delayed signal may be played back multiple times to create the sound of a repeating, decaying echo. Delay effects range from a subtle echo effect to a pronounced blending of previous sounds with new sounds.

properties.name: dry
properties.description: Output percent of original sound. At 0, only delayed sounds are output. Value can range from 0 to 1. Default value: [code]1[/code].

properties.name: feedback/active
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] feedback is enabled. Default value: [code]false[/code].

properties.name: feedback/delay_ms
properties.description: Feedback delay time in milliseconds. Default value: [code]340[/code].

properties.name: feedback/level_db
properties.description: Sound level for [code]tap1[/code]. Default value: [code]-6 dB[/code].

properties.name: feedback/lowpass
properties.description: Low-pass filter for feedback. Frequencies below the Low Cut value are filtered out of the source signal. Default value: [code]16000[/code].

properties.name: tap1/active
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], [code]tap1[/code] will be enabled. Default value: [code]true[/code].

properties.name: tap1/delay_ms
properties.description: [b]Tap1[/b] delay time in milliseconds. Default value: [code]250ms[/code].

properties.name: tap1/level_db
properties.description: Sound level for [code]tap1[/code]. Default value: [code]-6 dB[/code].

properties.name: tap1/pan
properties.description: Pan position for [code]tap1[/code]. Value can range from -1 (fully left) to 1 (fully right). Default value: [code]0.2[/code].

properties.name: tap2/active
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], [code]tap2[/code] will be enabled. Default value: [code]true[/code].

properties.name: tap2/delay_ms
properties.description: [b]Tap2[/b] delay time in milliseconds. Default value: [code]500ms[/code].

properties.name: tap2/level_db
properties.description: Sound level for [code]tap2[/code]. Default value: [code]-12 dB[/code].

properties.name: tap2/pan
properties.description: Pan position for [code]tap2[/code]. Value can range from -1 (fully left) to 1 (fully right). Default value: [code]-0.4[/code].

Directory.name: Directory
Directory.brief_description: Type used to handle the filesystem.

methods.name: change_dir
methods.description:
Change the currently opened directory to the one passed as an argument. The argument can be relative to the current directory (e.g. [code]newdir[/code] or [code]../newdir[/code]), or an absolute path (e.g. [code]/tmp/newdir[/code] or [code]res://somedir/newdir[/code]).
				The method returns one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK or ERR_*).

methods.name: copy
methods.description:
Copy the [i]from[/i] file to the [i]to[/i] destination. Both arguments should be paths to files, either relative or absolute. If the destination file exists and is not access-protected, it will be overwritten.
				Returns one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK, FAILED or ERR_*).

methods.name: current_is_dir
methods.description: Return whether the current item processed with the last [method get_next] call is a directory ([code].[/code] and [code]..[/code] are considered directories).

methods.name: dir_exists
methods.description: Return whether the target directory exists. The argument can be relative to the current directory, or an absolute path.

methods.name: file_exists
methods.description: Return whether the target file exists. The argument can be relative to the current directory, or an absolute path.

methods.name: get_current_dir
methods.description: Return the absolute path to the currently opened directory (e.g. [code]res://folder[/code] or [code]C:\tmp\folder[/code]).

methods.name: get_current_drive
methods.description: Returns the currently opened directory's drive index. See [method get_drive] to convert returned index to the name of the drive.

methods.name: get_drive
methods.description: On Windows, return the name of the drive (partition) passed as an argument (e.g. [code]C:[/code]). On other platforms, or if the requested drive does not existed, the method returns an empty String.

methods.name: get_drive_count
methods.description: On Windows, return the number of drives (partitions) mounted on the current filesystem. On other platforms, the method returns 0.

methods.name: get_next
methods.description:
Return the next element (file or directory) in the current directory (including [code].[/code] and [code]..[/code], unless [code]skip_navigational[/code] was given to [method list_dir_begin]).
				The name of the file or directory is returned (and not its full path). Once the stream has been fully processed, the method returns an empty String and closes the stream automatically (i.e. [method list_dir_end] would not be mandatory in such a case).

methods.name: get_space_left
methods.description: On Unix desktop systems, return the available space on the current directory's disk. On other platforms, this information is not available and the method returns 0 or -1.

methods.name: list_dir_begin
methods.description:
Initialise the stream used to list all files and directories using the [method get_next] function, closing the current opened stream if needed. Once the stream has been processed, it should typically be closed with [method list_dir_end].
				If you pass [code]skip_navigational[/code], then [code].[/code] and [code]..[/code] would be filtered out.
				If you pass [code]skip_hidden[/code], then hidden files would be filtered out.

methods.name: list_dir_end
methods.description: Close the current stream opened with [method list_dir_begin] (whether it has been fully processed with [method get_next] or not does not matter).

methods.name: make_dir
methods.description:
Create a directory. The argument can be relative to the current directory, or an absolute path. The target directory should be placed in an already existing directory (to create the full path recursively, see [method make_dir_recursive]).
				The method returns one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK, FAILED or ERR_*).

methods.name: make_dir_recursive
methods.description:
Create a target directory and all necessary intermediate directories in its path, by calling [method make_dir] recursively. The argument can be relative to the current directory, or an absolute path.
				Return one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK, FAILED or ERR_*).

methods.name: open
methods.description:
Open an existing directory of the filesystem. The [i]path[/i] argument can be within the project tree ([code]res://folder[/code]), the user directory ([code]user://folder[/code]) or an absolute path of the user filesystem (e.g. [code]/tmp/folder[/code] or [code]C:\tmp\folder[/code]).
				The method returns one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK or ERR_*).

methods.name: remove
methods.description:
Delete the target file or an empty directory. The argument can be relative to the current directory, or an absolute path. If the target directory is not empty, the operation will fail.
				Return one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK or FAILED).

methods.name: rename
methods.description:
Rename (move) the [i]from[/i] file to the [i]to[/i] destination. Both arguments should be paths to files, either relative or absolute. If the destination file exists and is not access-protected, it will be overwritten.
				Return one of the error code constants defined in [@Global Scope] (OK or FAILED).

Path.name: Path
Path.description: This class is a container/Node-ification of a [Curve3D], so it can have [Spatial] properties and [Node] info.

methods.name: get_curve
methods.description: Returns the [Curve3D] contained.

methods.name: set_curve
methods.description: Sets the [Curve3D].

World.name: World
World.brief_description: Class that has everything pertaining to a world.
World.description: Class that has everything pertaining to a world. A physics space, a visual scenario and a sound space. Spatial nodes register their resources into the current world.

properties.name: mid_height
properties.description: Height of the capsule mesh from the center point. Defaults to 1.0.

properties.name: radial_segments
properties.description: Number of radial segments on the capsule mesh. Defaults to 64.

properties.name: radius
properties.description: Radius of the capsule mesh. Defaults to 1.0.

properties.name: rings
properties.description: Number of rings along the height of the capsule. Defaults to 8.

TCP_Server.name: TCP_Server
TCP_Server.description: TCP Server class. Listens to connections on a port and returns a [StreamPeerTCP] when got a connection.

methods.name: is_connection_available
methods.description: Return true if a connection is available for taking.

methods.name: listen
methods.description:
Listen on the "port" binding to "bind_address".
				If "bind_address" is set as "*" (default), the server will listen on all available addresses (both IPv4 and IPv6).
				If "bind_address" is set as "0.0.0.0" (for IPv4) or "::" (for IPv6), the server will listen on all available addresses matching that IP type.
				If "bind_address" is set to any valid address (e.g. "192.168.1.101", "::1", etc), the server will only listen on the interface with that addresses (or fail if no interface with the given address exists).

methods.name: stop
methods.description: Stop listening.

methods.name: take_connection
methods.description: If a connection is available, return a StreamPeerTCP with the connection/

ConfigFile.name: ConfigFile
ConfigFile.brief_description: Helper class to handle INI-style files.
ConfigFile.description:
This helper class can be used to store [Variant] values on the filesystem using INI-style formatting. The stored values are indentified by a section and a key:
		[codeblock]
		[section]
		some_key=42
		string_example="Hello World!"
		a_vector=Vector3( 1, 0, 2 )
		[/codeblock]
		The stored data can be saved to or parsed from a file, though ConfigFile objects can also be used directly without accessing the filesystem.
		The following example shows how to parse an INI-style file from the system, read its contents and store new values in it:
		[codeblock]
		var config = ConfigFile.new()
		var err = config.load("user://settings.cfg")
		if err == OK: # if not, something went wrong with the file loading
		    # Look for the display/width pair, and default to 1024 if missing
		    var screen_width = get_value("display", "width", 1024)
		    # Store a variable if and only if it hasn't been defined yet
		    if not config.has_section_key("audio", "mute"):
		        config.set_value("audio", "mute", false)
		    # Save the changes by overwriting the previous file
		    config.save("user://settings.cfg")
		[/codeblock]

methods.name: erase_section
methods.description: Deletes the specified section along with all the key-value pairs inside.

methods.name: get_section_keys
methods.description: Returns an array of all defined key identifiers in the specified section.

methods.name: get_sections
methods.description: Returns an array of all defined section identifiers.

methods.name: get_value
methods.description: Returns the current value for the specified section and key. If the section and/or the key do not exist, the method returns the value of the optional [code]default[/code] argument, or [code]null[/code] if it is omitted.

methods.name: has_section
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the specified section exists.

methods.name: has_section_key
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if the specified section-key pair exists.

methods.name: load
methods.description: Loads the config file specified as a parameter. The file's contents are parsed and loaded in the ConfigFile object which the method was called on. Returns one of the [code]OK[/code], [code]FAILED[/code] or [code]ERR_*[/code] constants listed in [@Global Scope]. If the load was successful, the return value is [code]OK[/code].

methods.name: save
methods.description: Saves the contents of the ConfigFile object to the file specified as a parameter. The output file uses an INI-style structure. Returns one of the [code]OK[/code], [code]FAILED[/code] or [code]ERR_*[/code] constants listed in [@Global Scope]. If the load was successful, the return value is [code]OK[/code].

methods.name: set_value
methods.description: Assigns a value to the specified key of the the specified section. If the section and/or the key do not exist, they are created. Passing a [code]null[/code] value deletes the specified key if it exists, and deletes the section if it ends up empty once the key has been removed.

PopupMenu.name: PopupMenu
PopupMenu.brief_description: PopupMenu displays a list of options.
PopupMenu.description: PopupMenu is the typical Control that displays a list of options. They are popular in toolbars or context menus.

methods.name: add_check_item
methods.description: Add a new checkable item with text "label". An id can optionally be provided, as well as an accelerator. If no id is provided, one will be created from the index. Note that checkable items just display a checkmark, but don't have any built-in checking behavior and must be checked/unchecked manually.

methods.name: add_icon_check_item
methods.description:
Add a new checkable item with text "label" and icon "texture". An id can optionally be provided, as well as an accelerator. If no id is provided, one will be
				created from the index. Note that checkable items just display a checkmark, but don't have any built-in checking behavior and must be checked/unchecked manually.

methods.name: add_icon_item
methods.description: Add a new item with text "label" and icon "texture". An id can optionally be provided, as well as an accelerator keybinding. If no id is provided, one will be created from the index.

methods.name: add_item
methods.description: Add a new item with text "label". An id can optionally be provided, as well as an accelerator keybinding. If no id is provided, one will be created from the index.

methods.name: add_separator
methods.description: Add a separator between items. Separators also occupy an index.

methods.name: add_submenu_item
methods.description: Adds an item with a submenu. The submenu is the name of a child PopupMenu node that would be shown when the item is clicked. An id can optionally be provided, but if is isn't provided, one will be created from the index.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clear the popup menu, in effect removing all items.

methods.name: get_item_accelerator
methods.description: Return the accelerator of the item at index "idx". Accelerators are special combinations of keys that activate the item, no matter which control is focused.

methods.name: get_item_count
methods.description: Return the amount of items.

methods.name: get_item_icon
methods.description: Return the icon of the item at index "idx".

methods.name: get_item_id
methods.description: Return the id of the item at index "idx".

methods.name: get_item_index
methods.description: Find and return the index of the item containing a given id.

methods.name: get_item_metadata
methods.description: Return the metadata of an item, which might be of any type. You can set it with [method set_item_metadata], which provides a simple way of assigning context data to items.

methods.name: get_item_submenu
methods.description: Return the submenu name of the item at index "idx".

methods.name: get_item_text
methods.description: Return the text of the item at index "idx".

CollisionObject2D.name: CollisionObject2D
CollisionObject2D.description: CollisionObject2D is the base class for 2D physics objects. It can hold any number of 2D collision [Shape2D]\ s. Each shape must be assigned to a [i]shape owner[/i]. The CollisionObject2D can have any number of shape owners. Shape owners are not nodes and do not appear in the editor, but are accessible through code using the [code]shape_owner_*[/code] methods.

methods.name: create_shape_owner
methods.description: Creates a new shape owner for the given object. Returns [code]owner_id[/code] of the new owner for future reference.

methods.name: get_rid
methods.description: Returns the object's [RID].

methods.name: get_shape_owners
methods.description: Returns an [Array] of [code]owner_id[/code] identifiers. You can use these ids in other methods that take [code]owner_id[/code] as an argument.

methods.name: is_pickable
methods.description: Return whether this object is pickable.

methods.name: is_shape_owner_disabled
methods.description: If [code]true[/code] the shape owner and its shapes are disabled.

methods.name: remove_shape_owner
methods.description: Removes the given shape owner.

methods.name: set_pickable
methods.description: Set whether this object is pickable. A pickable object can detect the mouse pointer enter/leave it and, if the mouse is inside it, report input events.

methods.name: shape_find_owner
methods.description: Returns the [code]owner_id[/code] of the given shape.

methods.name: shape_owner_add_shape
methods.description: Adds a [Shape2D] to the shape owner.

methods.name: shape_owner_clear_shapes
methods.description: Removes all shapes from the shape owner.

methods.name: shape_owner_get_owner
methods.description: Returns the parent object of the given shape owner.

methods.name: shape_owner_get_shape
methods.description: Returns the [Shape2D] with the given id from the given shape owner.

methods.name: shape_owner_get_shape_count
methods.description: Returns the number of shapes the given shape owner contains.

methods.name: shape_owner_get_transform
methods.description: Returns the shape owner's [Transform2D].

methods.name: shape_owner_remove_shape
methods.description: Removes a shape from the given shape owner.

methods.name: shape_owner_set_disabled
methods.description: If [code]true[/code] disables the given shape owner.

methods.name: shape_owner_set_transform
methods.description: Sets the [Transform2D] of the given shape owner.

signals.name: input_event
signals.description: Emitted when an input event occurs and [code]input_pickable[/code] is [code]true[/code].

signals.name: mouse_entered
signals.description: Emitted when the mouse pointer enters any of this object's shapes.

signals.name: mouse_exited
signals.description: Emitted when the mouse pointer exits all this object's shapes.

properties.name: input_pickable
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] this object is pickable. A pickable object can detect the mouse pointer entering/leaving, and if the mouse is inside it, report input events.

VSlider.name: VSlider
VSlider.description: Vertical slider. See [Slider]. This one goes from left (min) to right (max).

ARVRAnchor.name: ARVRAnchor
ARVRAnchor.description:
The ARVR Anchor point is a spatial node that maps a real world location identified by the AR platform to a position within the game world. For example, as long as plane detection in ARKit is on, ARKit will identify and update the position of planes (tables, floors, etc) and create anchors for them.
		This node is mapped to one of the anchors through its unique id. When you receive a signal that a new anchor is available you should add this node to your scene for that anchor. You can predefine nodes and set the id and the nodes will simply remain on 0,0,0 until a plane is recognised.
		Keep in mind that as long as plane detection is enable the size, placing and orientation of an anchor will be updates as the detection logic learns more about the real world out there especially if only part of the surface is in view.

methods.name: get_anchor_id
methods.description: Returns the anchor id for this anchor.

methods.name: get_anchor_name
methods.description: Returns the name given to this anchor.

methods.name: get_is_active
methods.description: Returns true if the anchor is being tracked and false if no anchor with this id is currently known.

methods.name: get_plane
methods.description: Returns a plane aligned with our anchor, handy for intersection testing

methods.name: get_size
methods.description: Returns the estimated size of the plane that was detected. Say when the anchor relates to a table in the real world, this is the estimated size of the surface of that table.

methods.name: set_anchor_id
methods.description: Binds this anchor node to an anchor with this id. You can set this before the anchor itself exists. The first anchor that is identified gets id 1, the second id 2, etc. When anchors get removed that slot remains free and can be assigned to the next anchor that is identified. The most common situation where anchors 'disappear' is when the AR server identifies that two anchors represent different parts of the same plane and merge them.

PathFollow2D.name: PathFollow2D
PathFollow2D.description:
This node takes its parent [Path2D], and returns the coordinates of a point within it, given a distance from the first vertex.
		It is useful for making other nodes follow a path, without coding the movement pattern. For that, the nodes must be descendants of this node. Then, when setting an offset in this node, the descendant nodes will move accordingly.

methods.name: get_cubic_interpolation
methods.description: This method returns whether the position between two cached points (see [method set_cubic_interpolation]) is interpolated linearly, or cubicly.

methods.name: get_h_offset
methods.description: Returns the horizontal displacement this node has from its parent [Path2D].

methods.name: get_offset
methods.description: Returns the distance along the path in pixels.

methods.name: get_unit_offset
methods.description: Returns the distance along the path as a number in the range 0.0 (for the first vertex) to 1.0 (for the last).

methods.name: get_v_offset
methods.description: Returns the vertical displacement this node has from its parent [Path2D].

methods.name: has_loop
methods.description: Returns whether this node wraps its offsets around, or truncates them to the path ends.

methods.name: is_rotating
methods.description: Returns whether this node rotates to follow the path.

methods.name: set_cubic_interpolation
methods.description:
The points along the [Curve2D] of the [Path2D] are precomputed before use, for faster calculations. The point at the requested offset is then calculated interpolating between two adjacent cached points. This may present a problem if the curve makes sharp turns, as the cached points may not follow the curve closely enough.
				There are two answers to this problem: Either increase the number of cached points and increase memory consumption, or make a cubic interpolation between two points at the cost of (slightly) slower calculations.
				This method controls whether the position between two cached points is interpolated linearly, or cubicly.

methods.name: set_h_offset
methods.description:
Moves this node horizontally. As this node's position will be set every time its offset is set, this allows many PathFollow2D to share the same curve (and thus the same movement pattern), yet not return the same position for a given path offset.
				A similar effect may be achieved moving this node's descendants.

methods.name: set_loop
methods.description: If set, any offset outside the path's length (whether set by [method set_offset] or [method set_unit_offset] will wrap around, instead of stopping at the ends. Set it for cyclic paths.

methods.name: set_offset
methods.description: Sets the distance from the first vertex, measured in pixels along the path. This sets this node's position to a point within the path.

methods.name: set_rotate
methods.description: If set, this node rotates to follow the path, making its descendants rotate.

methods.name: set_unit_offset
methods.description: Sets the distance from the first vertex, considering 0.0 as the first vertex and 1.0 as the last. This is just another way of expressing the offset within the path, as the offset supplied is multiplied internally by the path's length.

methods.name: set_v_offset
methods.description: Moves the PathFollow2D vertically, for the same reasons of [method set_h_offset].

VisibilityNotifier.name: VisibilityNotifier
VisibilityNotifier.brief_description: Detects when the node is visible on screen.
VisibilityNotifier.description: The VisibilityNotifier detects when it is visible on the screen. It also notifies when its bounding rectangle enters or exits the screen or a [Camera]'s view.

AtlasTexture.name: AtlasTexture
AtlasTexture.brief_description: Packs multiple small textures in a single, bigger one. Helps to optimize video memory costs and render calls.
AtlasTexture.description:
[Texture] resource aimed at managing big textures files that pack multiple smaller textures. Consists of a [Texture], a margin that defines the border width,
		and a region that defines the actual area of the AtlasTexture.

properties.name: atlas
properties.description: The texture that contains the atlas. Can be any [Texture] subtype.

properties.name: margin
properties.description: The margin around the region. The [Rect2]'s 'size' parameter ('w' and 'h' in the editor) resizes the texture so it fits within the margin.

properties.name: region
properties.description: The AtlasTexture's used region.

BitmapFont.name: BitmapFont
BitmapFont.description: Renders text using [code]*.fnt[/code] fonts containing texture atlases. Supports distance fields. For using vector font files like TTF directly, see [DynamicFont].

methods.name: add_char
methods.description: Adds a character to the font, where [code]character[/code] is the unicode value, [code]texture[/code] is the texture index, [code]rect[/code] is the region in the texture (in pixels!), [code]align[/code] is the (optional) alignment for the character and [code]advance[/code] is the (optional) advance.

methods.name: add_kerning_pair
methods.description: Adds a kerning pair to the [BitmapFont] as a difference. Kerning pairs are special cases where a typeface advance is determined by the next character.

methods.name: add_texture
methods.description: Adds a texture to the [BitmapFont].

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Clears all the font data and settings.

methods.name: create_from_fnt
methods.description: Creates a BitmapFont from the [code]*.fnt[/code] file at [code]path[/code].

methods.name: get_char_size
methods.description: Returns the size of a character, optionally taking kerning into account if the next character is provided.

methods.name: get_fallback
methods.description: Returns the fallback BitmapFont.

methods.name: get_kerning_pair
methods.description: Returns a kerning pair as a difference.

methods.name: get_texture
methods.description: Returns the font atlas texture at index [code]idx[/code].

methods.name: get_texture_count
methods.description: Returns the number of textures in the BitmapFont atlas.

methods.name: set_ascent
methods.description: Sets the font ascent (number of pixels above the baseline).

methods.name: set_distance_field_hint
methods.description: If [code]true[/code] distance field hint is enabled.

methods.name: set_fallback
methods.description: Sets the fallback BitmapFont.

methods.name: set_height
methods.description: Sets the total font height (ascent plus descent) in pixels.

properties.name: ascent
