properties.name: chars
properties.description: The characters in the BitmapFont.

properties.name: distance_field
properties.description: If [code]true[/code] distance field hint is enabled.

properties.name: fallback
properties.description: The fallback font.

properties.name: height
properties.description: Total font height (ascent plus descent) in pixels.

properties.name: kernings
properties.description: The font's kernings as [PoolIntArray].

properties.name: textures
properties.description: The font's [Texture]\ s.

EditorImportPlugin.name: EditorImportPlugin
EditorImportPlugin.brief_description: Registers a custom resource importer in the editor. Use the class to parse any file and import it as a new resource type.

methods.name: get_import_options
methods.description: Get the options and default values for the preset at this index. Returns an Array of Dictionaries with the following keys: "name", "default_value", "property_hint" (optional), "hint_string" (optional), "usage" (optional).

methods.name: get_importer_name
methods.description: Get the unique name of the importer.

methods.name: get_preset_count
methods.description: Get the number of initial presets defined by the plugin. Use [method get_import_options] to get the default options for the preset and [method get_preset_name] to get the name of the preset.

methods.name: get_preset_name
methods.description: Get the name of the options preset at this index.

methods.name: get_recognized_extensions
methods.description: Get the list of file extensions to associate with this loader (case insensitive). e.g. ["obj"].

methods.name: get_resource_type
methods.description: Get the godot resource type associated with this loader. e.g. "Mesh" or "Animation".

methods.name: get_save_extension
methods.description: Get the extension used to save this resource in the [code].import[/code] directory.

methods.name: get_visible_name
methods.description: Get the name to display in the import window.

SpriteFrames.name: SpriteFrames
SpriteFrames.description: Sprite frame library for [AnimatedSprite]. Contains frames and animation data for playback.

methods.name: add_animation
methods.description: Adds a new animation to the the library.

methods.name: add_frame
methods.description: Adds a frame to the given animation.

methods.name: clear
methods.description: Removes all frames from the given animation.

methods.name: clear_all
methods.description: Removes all animations. A "default" animation will be created.

methods.name: get_animation_loop
methods.description: If [code]true[/code] the given animation will loop.

methods.name: get_animation_speed
methods.description: The animation's speed in frames per second.

methods.name: get_frame
methods.description: Returns the animation's selected frame.

methods.name: get_frame_count
methods.description: Returns the number of frames in the animation.

methods.name: has_animation
methods.description: If [code]true[/code] the named animation exists.

methods.name: remove_animation
methods.description: Removes the given animation.

methods.name: remove_frame
methods.description: Removes the animation's selected frame.

methods.name: rename_animation
methods.description: Changes the animation's name to [code]newname[/code].

methods.name: set_animation_loop
methods.description: If [code]true[/code] the animation will loop.

methods.name: set_animation_speed
methods.description: The animation's speed in frames per second.

methods.name: set_frame
methods.description: Sets the texture of the given frame.

properties.name: animations
properties.description: An [Array] containing the [code]name[/code], [code]speed[/code], [code]loop[/code], and [code]frames[/code] of each animation.

AnimationPlayer.name: AnimationPlayer
AnimationPlayer.description: An animation player is used for general purpose playback of [Animation] resources. It contains a dictionary of animations (referenced by name) and custom blend times between their transitions. Additionally, animations can be played and blended in different channels.

methods.name: add_animation
methods.description: Add an animation resource to the player, which will be later referenced by the "name" argument.

methods.name: advance
methods.description: Used to skip ahead or skip back in an animation. Delta is the time in seconds to skip.

methods.name: animation_get_next
methods.description: Return the name of the next animation in the queue.

methods.name: animation_set_next
methods.description: Set the name of an animation that will be played after.

methods.name: clear_caches
methods.description: The animation player creates caches for faster access to the nodes it will animate. However, if a specific node is removed, it may not notice it, so clear_caches will force the player to search for the nodes again.

methods.name: clear_queue
methods.description: If animations are queued to play, clear them.

methods.name: find_animation
methods.description: Find an animation name by resource.

methods.name: get_animation
methods.description: Get an [Animation] resource by requesting a name.

methods.name: get_animation_list
methods.description: Get the list of names of the animations stored in the player.

methods.name: get_animation_process_mode
methods.description: Return the mode in which the animation player processes. See [method set_animation_process_mode].

methods.name: get_autoplay
methods.description: Return the name of the animation that will be automatically played when the scene is loaded.

methods.name: get_blend_time
methods.description: Get the blend time between two animations, referenced by their names.

methods.name: get_current_animation
methods.description: Return the name of the animation being played.

methods.name: get_current_animation_length
methods.description: Get the length (in seconds) of the currently being played animation.

methods.name: get_current_animation_position
methods.description: Get the position (in seconds) of the currently being played animation.

methods.name: get_default_blend_time
methods.description: Return the default blend time between animations.

methods.name: get_position
methods.description: Return the playback position (in seconds) in an animation channel (or channel 0 if none is provided).

methods.name: get_root
methods.description: Return path to root node (see [method set_root]).

methods.name: get_speed_scale
methods.description: Get the speed scaling ratio in a given animation channel (or channel 0 if none is provided). Default ratio is [i]1[/i] (no scaling).

methods.name: has_animation
methods.description: Request whether an [Animation] name exist within the player.

methods.name: is_active
methods.description: Return true if the player is active.

methods.name: is_playing
methods.description: Return whether an animation is playing.

methods.name: play
methods.description: Play a given animation by the animation name. Custom speed and blend times can be set. If custom speed is negative (-1), 'from_end' being true can play the animation backwards.

methods.name: play_backwards
methods.description: Play a given animation by the animation name in reverse.

methods.name: queue
methods.description: Queue an animation for playback once the current one is done.

methods.name: remove_animation
methods.description: Remove an animation from the player (by supplying the same name used to add it).

methods.name: rename_animation
methods.description: Rename an existing animation.

methods.name: seek
methods.description: Seek the animation to a given position in time (in seconds). If 'update' is true, the animation will be updated too, otherwise it will be updated at process time.

methods.name: set_active
methods.description: Set the player as active (playing). If false, it will do nothing.

methods.name: set_animation_process_mode
methods.description: Set the mode in which the animation player processes. By default, it processes on idle time (framerate dependent), but using fixed time works well for animating static collision bodies in 2D and 3D. See enum ANIMATION_PROCESS_*.

methods.name: set_autoplay
methods.description: Set the name of the animation that will be automatically played when the scene is loaded.

methods.name: set_blend_time
methods.description: Specify a blend time (in seconds) between two animations, referenced by their names.

methods.name: set_current_animation
methods.description: Set the current animation (even if no playback occurs). Using set_current_animation() and set_active() are similar to calling play().

methods.name: set_default_blend_time
methods.description: Set the default blend time between animations.

methods.name: set_root
methods.description: AnimationPlayer resolves animation track paths from this node (which is relative to itself), by default root is "..", but it can be changed.

methods.name: set_speed_scale
methods.description: Set a speed scaling ratio in a given animation channel (or channel 0 if none is provided). Default ratio is [i]1[/i] (no scaling).

methods.name: stop
methods.description: Stop the currently playing animation.

methods.name: stop_all
methods.description: Stop playback of animations (deprecated).

signals.name: animation_changed
signals.description: If the currently being played animation changes, this signal will notify of such change.

signals.name: animation_finished
signals.description: Notifies when an animation finished playing.

signals.name: animation_started
signals.description: Notifies when an animation starts playing.

constants.name: ANIMATION_PROCESS_PHYSICS
constants.description: Process animation during the physics process. This is specially useful when animating physics bodies.

constants.name: ANIMATION_PROCESS_IDLE
constants.description: Process animation during the idle process.

RichTextLabel.name: RichTextLabel
RichTextLabel.description: Label that displays rich text. Rich text can contain custom text, fonts, images and some basic formatting. It also adapts itself to given width/heights.

methods.name: is_selection_enabled

methods.name: set_selection_enabled

Label.name: Label
Label.brief_description: Displays plain text in a line or wrapped inside a rectangle. For formatted text, use [RichTextLabel].
Label.description: Label displays plain text on the screen. It gives you control over the horizontal and vertical alignment, and can wrap the text inside the node's bounding rectangle. It doesn't support bold, italics or other formatting. For that, use [RichTextLabel] instead.

methods.name: get_align

methods.name: get_line_count
methods.description: Returns the amount of lines of text the Label has.

methods.name: get_line_height
methods.description: Returns the font size in pixels.

methods.name: get_lines_skipped
methods.description: Returns the the number of lines to skip before displaying.

methods.name: get_max_lines_visible

methods.name: get_percent_visible

methods.name: get_text

methods.name: get_total_character_count
methods.description: Returns the total length of the text.

methods.name: get_valign
methods.description: Returns the vertical alignment mode (any of the VALIGN_* enumeration values).

methods.name: get_visible_characters
methods.description: Returns the restricted number of characters to display. Returns -1 if unrestricted.

methods.name: get_visible_line_count
methods.description: Returns the number of lines shown. Useful if the [code]Label[/code] 's height cannot currently display all lines.

methods.name: has_autowrap
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if [i]autowrap[/i] mode (see [method set_autowrap]).

methods.name: is_clipping_text
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if text would be cut off if it is too wide.

methods.name: is_uppercase
methods.description: Returns [code]true[/code] if text is displayed in all capitals.

methods.name: set_align
methods.description: Sets the alignment mode to any of the ALIGN_* enumeration values.

methods.name: set_autowrap
methods.description: Set [i]autowrap[/i] mode. When enabled, autowrap will fit text to the control width, breaking sentences when they exceed the available horizontal space. When disabled, the label minimum width becomes the width of the longest row, and the minimum height large enough to fit all rows.

methods.name: set_clip_text
methods.description: Cuts off the rest of the text if it is too wide.

methods.name: set_lines_skipped
methods.description: Sets the number of lines to skip before displaying. Useful for scrolling text.

methods.name: set_max_lines_visible
methods.description: Restricts the number of lines to display. Set to -1 to disable.

methods.name: set_percent_visible
methods.description: Restricts the number of characters to display (as a percentage of the total text).

methods.name: set_text
methods.description: Set the label text. Text can contain newlines.

methods.name: set_uppercase
methods.description: Display text in all capitals.

methods.name: set_valign
methods.description: Sets the vertical alignment mode to any of the VALIGN_* enumeration values.

methods.name: set_visible_characters
methods.description: Restricts the number of characters to display. Set to -1 to disable.

constants.name: ALIGN_LEFT
constants.description: Align rows to the left (default).

constants.name: ALIGN_CENTER
constants.description: Align rows centered.

constants.name: ALIGN_RIGHT
constants.description: Align rows to the right (default).

constants.name: ALIGN_FILL
constants.description: Expand row whitespaces to fit the width.

constants.name: VALIGN_TOP
constants.description: Align the whole text to the top.

constants.name: VALIGN_CENTER
constants.description: Align the whole text to the center.

constants.name: VALIGN_BOTTOM
constants.description: Align the whole text to the bottom.

constants.name: VALIGN_FILL
constants.description: Align the whole text by spreading the rows.

properties.name: align
properties.description: Controls the text's horizontal align. Supports left, center, right, and fill, or justify. Set it to one of the [code]ALIGN_*[/code] constants.

properties.name: autowrap
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], wraps the text inside the node's bounding rectangle. If you resize the node, it will change its height automatically to show all the text. Default: false.

properties.name: clip_text
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], the Label only shows the text that fits inside its bounding rectangle. It also lets you scale the node down freely.

properties.name: lines_skipped
properties.description: The node ignores the first [code]lines_skipped[/code] lines before it starts to display text.

properties.name: max_lines_visible
properties.description: Limits the lines of text the node shows on screen.

properties.name: percent_visible
properties.description: Limits the count of visible characters. If you set [code]percent_visible[/code] to 50, only up to half of the text's characters will display on screen. Useful to animate the text in a dialog box.

properties.name: text
properties.description: The text to display on screen.

properties.name: uppercase
properties.description: If [code]true[/code], all the text displays as UPPERCASE.

properties.name: valign
properties.description: Controls the text's vertical align. Supports top, center, bottom, and fill. Set it to one of the [code]VALIGN_*[/code] constants.

signals.name: screen_exited

signals.name: viewport_exited

methods.name: has_network_peer
methods.description: Returns true if there is a [NetworkedMultiplayerPeer] set (with [method SceneTree.set_network_peer]).

methods.name: is_network_server
methods.description: Returns true if this SceneTree's [NetworkedMultiplayerPeer] is in server mode (listening for connections).

methods.name: set_network_peer
methods.description: Set the peer object to handle the RPC system (effectively enabling networking). Depending on the peer itself, the SceneTree will become a network server (check with [method is_network_server()]) and will set root node's network mode to master (see NETWORK_MODE_* constants in [Node]), or it will become a regular peer with root node set to slave. All child nodes are set to inherit the network mode by default. Handling of networking-related events (connection, disconnection, new clients) is done by connecting to SceneTree's signals.

EditorScript.brief_description: Simple script to perform changes in the currently edited scene.
EditorScript.description: This script can be run from the Scene -> Run Script menu option.

WeakRef.name: WeakRef
WeakRef.brief_description: Holds an [Object], but does not contribute to the reference count if the object is a reference.
WeakRef.description: A weakref can hold a [Reference], without contributing to the reference counter. A weakref can be created from an [Object] using [method @GDScript.weakref]. If this object is not a reference, weakref still works, however, it does not have any effect on the object. Weakrefs are useful in cases where multiple classes have variables that refer to each other. Without weakrefs, using these classes could lead to memory leaks, since both references keep each other from being released. Making part of the variables a weakref can prevent this cyclic dependency, and allows the references to be released.

methods.name: get_ref
methods.description: Returns the [Object] this weakref is referring to.

ARVRInterface.name: ARVRInterface
ARVRInterface.brief_description: Base class for ARVR interface implementation.
ARVRInterface.description:
This class needs to be implemented to make an AR or VR platform available to Godot and these should be implemented as C++ modules or GDNative modules (note that for GDNative the subclass ARVRScriptInterface should be used). Part of the interface is exposed to GDScript so you can detect, enable and configure an AR or VR platform.
		Interfaces should be written in such a way that simply enabling them will give us a working setup. You can query the available interfaces through ARVRServer.

methods.name: get_anchor_detection_is_enabled
methods.description: Returns true if achor detection is enabled (AR only).

methods.name: get_capabilities
methods.description: Returns a combination of flags providing information about the capabilities of this interface.

methods.name: get_name
methods.description: Returns the name of this interface (OpenVR, OpenHMD, ARKit, etc).

methods.name: get_recommended_render_targetsize
methods.description: Returns the resolution at which we should render our intermediate results before things like lens distortion are applied by the VR platform.

methods.name: get_tracking_status
methods.description: If supported, returns the status of our tracking. This will allow you to provide feedback to the user whether there are issues with positional tracking.

methods.name: initialize
methods.description:
Call this to initialize this interface. The first interface that is initialized is identified as the primary interface and it will be used for rendering output.
				After initializing the interface you want to use you then need to enable the AR/VR mode of a viewport and rendering should commence. 
				Note that you must enable the AR/VR mode on the main viewport for any device that uses the main output of Godot such as for mobile VR. 
				If you do this for a platform that handles its own output (such as OpenVR) Godot will show just one eye without distortion on screen. Alternatively you can add a separate viewport node to your scene and enable AR/VR on that viewport and it will be used to output to the HMD leaving you free to do anything you like in the main window such as using a separate camera as a spectator camera or render out something completely different.
				While currently not used you can activate additional interfaces, you may wish to do this if you want to track controllers from other platforms. However at this point in time only one interface can render to an HMD.

methods.name: is_initialized
methods.description: Returns true if this interface is active.

methods.name: is_primary
methods.description: Returns true if this interface is currently the primary interface (the interface responsible for showing the output).

methods.name: is_stereo
methods.description: Returns true if the current output of this interface is in stereo.

methods.name: set_anchor_detection_is_enabled
methods.description: Enables anchor detection, this is used on AR interfaces and enables the extra logic that will detect planes, features, objects, etc. and adds/modifies anchor points.

methods.name: set_is_initialized
methods.description: Initialize/uninitialize this interface (same effect as calling initialize/uninitialize).

methods.name: set_is_primary
methods.description: Set this interface to the primary interface (unset the old one).

methods.name: uninitialize
methods.description: Turns the interface off.

constants.name: ARVR_NONE
constants.description: No ARVR capabilities.

constants.name: ARVR_MONO
constants.description: This interface can work with normal rendering output (non-HMD based AR).

constants.name: ARVR_STEREO
constants.description: This interface supports stereoscopic rendering.

constants.name: ARVR_AR
constants.description: This interface support AR (video background and real world tracking).

constants.name: ARVR_EXTERNAL
constants.description: This interface outputs to an external device, if the main viewport is used the on screen output is an unmodified buffer of either the left or right eye (stretched if the viewport size is not changed to the same aspect ratio of get_recommended_render_targetsize. Using a seperate viewport node frees up the main viewport for other purposes.

constants.name: EYE_MONO
constants.description: Mono output, this is mostly used internally when retrieving positioning information for our camera node or when stereo scopic rendering is not supported.

constants.name: EYE_LEFT
constants.description: Left eye output, this is mostly used internally when rendering the image for the left eye and obtaining positioning and projection information.

constants.name: EYE_RIGHT
constants.description: Right eye output, this is mostly used internally when rendering the image for the right eye and obtaining positioning and projection information.

constants.name: ARVR_NORMAL_TRACKING
constants.description: Tracking is behaving as expected.

constants.name: ARVR_EXCESSIVE_MOTION
constants.description: Tracking is hindered by excessive motion, player is moving faster then tracking can keep up.

constants.name: ARVR_INSUFFICIENT_FEATURES
constants.description: Tracking is hindered by insufficient features, it's too dark (for camera based tracking), player is blocked, etc.

constants.name: ARVR_UNKNOWN_TRACKING
constants.description: We don't know the status of the tracking or this interface does not provide feedback.

constants.name: ARVR_NOT_TRACKING
constants.description: Tracking is not functional (camera not plugged in or obscured, lighthouses turned off, etc.)

properties.name: ar_is_anchor_detection_enabled
properties.description: On an AR interface, is our anchor detection enabled?

properties.name: interface_is_initialized
properties.description: Has this interface been initialized?

properties.description: Is this our primary interface?

PopupDialog.description: PopupDialog is a base class for popup dialogs, along with [WindowDialog].

Object.name: Object
Object.brief_description: Base class for all non built-in types.
Object.description:
Base class for all non built-in types. Everything not a built-in type starts the inheritance chain from this class.
		Objects do not manage memory, if inheriting from one the object will most likely have to be deleted manually (call the [method free] function from the script or delete from C++).
		Some derivatives add memory management, such as [Reference] (which keeps a reference count and deletes itself automatically when no longer referenced) and [Node], which deletes the children tree when deleted.
		Objects export properties, which are mainly useful for storage and editing, but not really so much in programming. Properties are exported in [method _get_property_list] and handled in [method _get] and [method _set]. However, scripting languages and C++ have simpler means to export them.
		Objects also receive notifications ([method _notification]). Notifications are a simple way to notify the object about simple events, so they can all be handled together.

methods.name: _get
methods.description: Return a property, return null if the property does not exist.

methods.name: _get_property_list
methods.description: Return the property list, array of dictionaries, dictionaries must contain: name:String, type:int (see TYPE_* enum in [@Global Scope]) and optionally: hint:int (see PROPERTY_HINT_* in [@Global Scope]), hint_string:String, usage:int (see PROPERTY_USAGE_* in [@Global Scope]).

methods.name: _notification
methods.description: Notification request, the notification id is received.

methods.name: _set
methods.description: Set a property. Return true if the property was found.

methods.name: add_user_signal
methods.description: Add a user signal (can be added anytime). Arguments are optional, but can be added as an array of dictionaries, each containing "name" and "type" (from [@Global Scope] TYPE_*).

methods.name: can_translate_messages
methods.description: Return true if this object can translate strings.

methods.name: connect
methods.description: Connect a signal to a method at a target (member function). Binds are optional and are passed as extra arguments to the call. Flags specify optional deferred or one shot connections, see enum CONNECT_*. A signal can only be connected once to a method, and it will throw an error if already connected. If you want to avoid this, use [method is_connected] to check.

methods.name: disconnect
methods.description: Disconnect a signal from a method.

methods.name: get
methods.description: Get a property from the object.

methods.name: get_class
methods.description: Return the class of the object as a string.

methods.name: get_incoming_connections
methods.description:
Returns an [Array] of dictionaries with information about signals that are connected to this object.
				Inside each [Dictionary] there are 3 fields:
				- "source" is a reference to signal emitter.
				- "signal_name" is name of connected signal.
				- "method_name" is a name of method to which signal is connected.

methods.name: get_instance_id
methods.description: Return the instance ID. All objects have a unique instance ID.

methods.name: get_meta
methods.description: Return a metadata from the object.

methods.name: get_meta_list
methods.description: Return the list of metadata in the object.

methods.name: get_property_list
methods.description: Return the list of properties as an array of dictionaries, dictionaries contain: name:String, type:int (see TYPE_* enum in [@Global Scope]) and optionally: hint:int (see PROPERTY_HINT_* in [@Global Scope]), hint_string:String, usage:int (see PROPERTY_USAGE_* in [@Global Scope]).

methods.name: get_script
methods.description: Return the object script (or null if it doesn't have one).

methods.name: get_signal_list
methods.description: Return the list of signals as an array of dictionaries.

methods.name: has_meta
methods.description: Return true if a metadata is found with the requested name.

methods.name: is_blocking_signals
methods.description: Return true if signal emission blocking is enabled.

methods.name: is_class
methods.description: Check the class of the object against a string (including inheritance).

methods.name: is_connected
methods.description: Return true if a connection exists for a given signal and target/method.

methods.name: notification
methods.description: Notify the object of something.

methods.name: set
methods.description: Set property into the object.

methods.name: set_block_signals
methods.description: If set to true, signal emission is blocked.

methods.name: set_message_translation
methods.description: Define whether this object can translate strings (with calls to [method tr]). Default is true.

methods.name: set_meta
methods.description: Set a metadata into the object. Metadata is serialized. Metadata can be [i]anything[/i].

methods.name: set_script
methods.description: Set a script into the object, scripts extend the object functionality.

methods.name: tr
methods.description: Translate a message. Only works if message translation is enabled (which it is by default). See [method set_message_translation].

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_POSTINITIALIZE
constants.description: Called right when the object is initialized. Not available in script.

constants.name: NOTIFICATION_PREDELETE
constants.description: Called before the object is about to be deleted.

constants.name: CONNECT_DEFERRED
constants.description: Connect a signal in deferred mode. This way, signal emissions are stored in a queue, then set on idle time.

constants.name: CONNECT_PERSIST
constants.description: Persisting connections are saved when the object is serialized to file.

constants.name: CONNECT_ONESHOT
constants.description: One shot connections disconnect themselves after emission.

PHashTranslation.name: PHashTranslation
PHashTranslation.description: Optimized translation. Uses real-time compressed translations, which results in very small dictionaries.

AudioEffectPhaser.name: AudioEffectPhaser
AudioEffectPhaser.brief_description:
Adds a Phaser audio effect to an Audio bus.
		Combines the original signal with a copy that is slightly out of phase with the original.
AudioEffectPhaser.description: Combines phase-shifted signals with the original signal. The movement of the phase-shifted signals is controlled using a Low Frequency Oscillator.

properties.name: depth
properties.description: Governs how high the filter frequencies sweep. Low value will primarily affect bass frequencies. High value can sweep high into the treble. Value can range from 0.1 to 4. Default value: [code]1[/code].

properties.name: feedback
properties.description: Output percent of modified sound. Value can range from 0.1 to 0.9. Default value: [code]0.7[/code].

properties.name: range_max_hz
properties.description: Determines the maximum frequency affected by the LFO modulations. Value can range from 10 to 10000. Default value: [code]1600hz[/code].

properties.name: range_min_hz
properties.description: Determines the minimum frequency affected by the LFO modulations. Value can range from 10 to 10000. Default value: [code]440hz[/code].

properties.name: rate_hz
properties.description: Adjusts the rate at which the effect sweeps up and down across the frequency range.

Rect2.name: Rect2
Rect2.description: Rect2 provides an 2D Axis-Aligned Bounding Box. It consists of a position, a size, and several utility functions. It is typically used for fast overlap tests.

methods.name: encloses

methods.name: expand
